{"title_page": "Jesus Is King", "text_new": "{{For|the accompanying concert film of the same name|Jesus Is King (film)}}\n{{Redirect|Jesus Is Lord|the credal affirmation|Jesus is Lord}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Jesus Is King\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[Kanye West]]\n| cover        = Kanye West - Jesus Is King.png\n| alt          = A blue LP vinyl with yellow lettering of the \"Jesus Is King\" album.\n| released     = October 25, 2019\n| recorded     = August 2018 \u2013 October 2019\n| studio       = \n| genre        = {{hlist|[[Christian hip hop]]|[[Gospel music|gospel]]}}<!--Gospel songs such as \"Water\", \"Selah\", \"Every Hour\", cited by reliable sources. This makes it a secondary genre for the infobox and only one source said \"gospel album in the same way a square is a rectangle.\"-->\n| length       = 27:04\n| label        =\n* [[GOOD Music|GOOD]]\n* [[Def Jam Recordings|Def Jam]]\n| producer     =\n* Kanye West\n* Angel Lopez\n*BoogzDaBeast\n*Brian \"AllDay\" Miller\n*Budgie\n*DrtWrk\n*[[E*vax]]\n*Federico Vindver\n*[[Finatik N Zac|FNZ]]\n*[[Labrinth]]\n*Michael Cerda\n*[[Ronny J]]\n*[[Timbaland]]\n*[[Warryn Campbell]]\n*Xcelence\n| prev_title   = [[Kids See Ghosts (album)|Kids See Ghosts]]\n| prev_year    = 2018\n| year         = 2019\n| next_title   = [[Jesus Is Born]]\n| next_year    = 2019\n| misc         = {{Singles\n | name        = Jesus Is King\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Follow God]]\n | single1date = November 12, 2019\n | single2     = [[Closed on Sunday]]\n | single2date = November 28, 2019\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Jesus Is King''''' <!--don't mention it being stylized in all caps per [[Wikipedia talk:WikiProject Albums/Archive 59#Why do we note all-caps stylisation?]]--> is the ninth studio album by American recording artist [[Kanye West]]. It was released on October 25, 2019, through [[GOOD Music]] and distributed by [[Def Jam Recordings]]. The album follows a [[Christianity|Christian]] theme, with West describing it as \"an expression of [[the gospel]].\" West had formed his [[Gospel music|gospel]] group the [[Sunday Service Choir]] in January 2019, performing gospel songs and covers of songs from West's discography. The song \"[[Water (Kanye West song)|Water]]\" was performed live prior to release by the group.\n\n''Jesus Is King'' features guest appearances from [[Clipse]], [[Ty Dolla Sign]], [[Kenny G]], [[Fred Hammond]], [[Ant Clemons]], and the Sunday Service Choir. Production is included from West, [[Benny Blanco]], BoogzDaBeast, [[Francis Starlite]], [[Pi'erre Bourne]], and [[Timbaland]], among others. West quit taking medication for his [[bipolar disorder]] and began recording the album in August 2018, originally announcing it as ''Yandhi''. The album missed two initial release dates in September and November 2018 under the original title, before being delayed indefinitely.\n\nIn August 2019, West's wife [[Kim Kardashian]] reannounced ''Yandhi'' as ''Jesus Is King'', but it missed two planned release dates for late September 2019 under the new title. The final release was simultaneous with that of a [[concert film]] [[Jesus Is King (film)|of the same name]], which included a number of the tracks as part of the soundtrack. \"[[Follow God]]\" was released as the lead single in November 2019, followed by \"[[Closed on Sunday]]\" later that same month. The album received mixed reviews from music critics. Some praised it in comparison to West's previous solo album ''[[Ye (album)|Ye]]'' and complemented the composition, while other critics expressed negative feelings towards the lyrical content and the inconsistency of ideas.\n\n''Jesus Is King'' stood as West's record-equaling ninth consecutive album to debut atop the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]. With the release, West became the first artist to occupy all top ten spots on the US [[Christian Songs]] and [[Billboard charts|Gospel Songs]] charts, respectively. West broke another record at the same time by being the first artist to simultaneously top five separate US charts: the ''Billboard'' 200, [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]], [[Top Rap Albums]], [[List of number-one Billboard Christian Albums|Top Christian Albums]] and [[Top Gospel Albums]]. The album was a chart topper in eight other countries, including Australia and Canada, while attaining top five positions in the Czech Republic, Finland, Ireland, the Netherlands, Sweden, and the United Kingdom. A companion album, ''[[Jesus Is Born]]'', was released in December 2019 by the Sunday Service Choir, and West's collaborative sequel album ''[[Jesus Is King Part II]]'' with [[Dr. Dre]] is slated for a future release.\n\n==Background and recording==\n===August \u2013 November 2018: ''Yandhi'', Chicago and Uganda===\nThroughout May and June 2018, five seven-track albums produced by West at his ranch in [[Jackson Hole, Wyoming]] were successively released as the Wyoming Sessions. [[Pusha T]]'s third studio album ''[[Daytona (album)|Daytona]]'' was released first, followed by West's eighth studio album ''[[Ye (album)|Ye]]'', West's collaborative studio album ''[[Kids See Ghosts (album)|Kids See Ghosts]]'', with [[Kid Cudi]] as [[Kids See Ghosts]], [[Nas]]' twelfth studio album ''[[Nasir (album)|Nasir]]'', and [[Teyana Taylor]]'s second studio album ''[[K.T.S.E.]]''; all of the albums were released in 2018. On ''Ye'', West acknowledged his [[bipolar disorder]] diagnosis. He stopped taking his medication for the disorder in June 2018 during the rollout of the Wyoming Sessions albums.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2018/12/kanye-mental-health/|title=Kanye: \"6 months off meds I can feel me again\"|date=December 15, 2018|accessdate=March 11, 2019|magazine=[[Consequence of Sound]]|first=Alex|last=Young|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215215103/https://consequenceofsound.net/2018/12/kanye-mental-health/|archive-date=December 15, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/bryanrolli/2018/12/13/nicki-minaj-kanye-west-tekashi-6ix9ine-worst-album-rollout-2018/|title=Nicki Minaj, Kanye West, Tekashi 6ix9ine: Which Rapper Had The Worst Album Rollout Of 2018?|magazine=[[Forbes]]|date=December 13, 2018|first=Bryan|last=Rolli|accessdate=September 19, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181214123613/https://www.forbes.com/sites/bryanrolli/2018/12/13/nicki-minaj-kanye-west-tekashi-6ix9ine-worst-album-rollout-2018/|archive-date=December 14, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, Chicago music artist [[Chance the Rapper]] announced that West was coming to Chicago to produce for his seven-track debut studio album.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8465190/chance-the-rapper-kanye-west-chicago-produce-new-album|title=Chance the Rapper Says Kanye West Is Heading to Chicago to Produce His New Album|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=July 12, 2018|first=Carl|last=Lamarre|accessdate=March 13, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180714091209/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8465190/chance-the-rapper-kanye-west-chicago-produce-new-album|archive-date=July 14, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>{{efn|Chance the Rapper's debut studio album ''[[The Big Day (album)|The Big Day]]'' was later released in July 2019 with no contributions from West.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tinymixtapes.com/news/chance-rapper-the-big-day-new-album|title=Chance The Rapper drops ''The Big Day'', featuring everyone but Kanye West|date=July 26, 2019|accessdate=September 9, 2019|website=[[Tiny Mix Tapes]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727021530/https://www.tinymixtapes.com/news/chance-rapper-the-big-day-new-album|archive-date=July 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>}} West was seen in the city at the end of August 2018, and simultaneously confirmed to [[Fox News]] that the two of them were recording music together.<ref name=\"August\">{{Cite news|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/entertainment/kanye-west-chicago-chance-the-rapper-album/|title=Kanye West in Chicago working with Chance the Rapper|date=August 29, 2018|accessdate=March 13, 2019|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|first=Alice|last=Bazerghi|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829193755/https://chicago.suntimes.com/entertainment/kanye-west-chicago-chance-the-rapper-album/|archive-date=August 29, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2018/08/kanye-chance-the-rapper-new-album/|title=Kanye in Chicago to work on Chance the Rapper's new album|date=August 30, 2018|accessdate=September 19, 2019|magazine=Consequence of Sound|first=Alex|last=Young|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180830084551/https://consequenceofsound.net/2018/08/kanye-chance-the-rapper-new-album/|archive-date=August 30, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> West later stated that his recording sessions with Chance the Rapper had helped the former reconnect with his roots and faith in [[Jesus in Christianity|Jesus]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/08/kanye-west-new-album-jesus-is-king-timeline/december-15-2018|title=Kanye West's Road From 'Yandhi' to 'Jesus Is King'|date=August 30, 2019|accessdate=September 9, 2019|website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|first=Jessica|last=McKinney|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190831145326/https://www.complex.com/music/2019/08/kanye-west-new-album-jesus-is-king-timeline/|archive-date=August 31, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The following month, West released the collaborative single \"[[I Love It (Kanye West and Lil Pump song)|I Love It]]\" with fellow rapper [[Lil Pump]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hot97.com/news/news/kanye-west-releases-brand-new-nsfw-single-i-love-it-ft-lil-pump-video|title=Kanye West Releases Brand New NSFW Single 'I Love It' ft. Lil' Pump [VIDEO]|last=Louie|first=King|date=September 7, 2018|publisher=[[WQHT|Hot 97]]|access-date=November 21, 2019}}</ref>{{efn|\"I Love It\" was later included on Lil Pump's second studio album ''[[Harverd Dropout]]'', released in February 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8499202/lil-pump-track-list-harverd-dropout|title=Lil Pump Shares 'Harverd Dropout' Track List Featuring Lil Wayne, Quavo & Lil Uzi Vert|date=February 20, 2019|accessdate= September 12, 2019|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|first=Michael|last=Saponara|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190220215314/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8499202/lil-pump-track-list-harverd-dropout|archive-date=February 20, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>}} In September 2018, West reactivated his [[Instagram]] account after a half-year absence,<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.thefader.com/2018/09/11/kanye-west-is-back-on-instagram|title=Kanye West is back on Instagram|date=September 11, 2018|accessdate=March 11, 2019|magazine=[[The Fader]]|first=Wandera|last=Hussein|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180912113232/https://www.thefader.com/2018/09/11/kanye-west-is-back-on-instagram|archive-date=September 12, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> with indications that he was working with American record producer [[Ronny J]], and Chance the Rapper, alongside the latter's brother [[Taylor Bennett (rapper)|Taylor Bennett]], and [[G Herbo]]. Through his Instagram, West confirmed that he was collaborating with fellow rapper [[6ix9ine]] and began posting snippets of new music.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://hiphopdx.com/news/id.48374/title.kanye-west-hits-the-studio-with-tekashi-6ix9ine#|title=Kanye West Confirms Tekashi 6ix9ine Collaboration|magazine=[[HipHopDX]]|date=September 11, 2018|first=Justin|last=Ivey|accessdate=September 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919171618/https://hiphopdx.com/news/id.48374/title.kanye-west-hits-the-studio-with-tekashi-6ix9ine|archive-date=September 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Snippet1\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.thefader.com/2018/09/14/kanye-west-new-music-snippet-instagram|magazine=The Fader|title=Kanye West shares new music snippet on Instagram|first=Jordan|last=Darville|date=September 14, 2018|accessdate=September 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919132523/https://www.thefader.com/2018/09/14/kanye-west-new-music-snippet-instagram|archive-date=September 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Snippet2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/kanye-west-previews-new-music-on-his-instagram-story-news.59735.html|title=Kanye West Previews New Music on His Instagram Story|first=Alex|last=Zidel|website=HotNewHipHop|date=September 14, 2018|accessdate=September 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919171530/https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/kanye-west-previews-new-music-on-his-instagram-story-news.59735.html|archive-date=September 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Ant Clemons]], who had previously worked with West on ''Ye'' and ''K.T.S.E.'', was invited to Chicago where he entered a studio room with West, Chance the Rapper, and American [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]] commentator [[Candace Owens]].<ref name=\"Ant\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-ant-clemons-904042/|title=Ant Clemons Went From Sleeping on Floors to Singing With Kanye West|author=Leight, Elia|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=29 October 2019|accessdate=20 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191105045958/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-ant-clemons-904042/|archive-date=November 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> During these Chicago sessions, Clemons recorded his vocals for \"[[Everything We Need]]\" and an earlier version of the track \"[[Selah (Kanye West song)|Selah]]\".<ref name=\"Ant\"/> West also announced that he was permanently moving back to Chicago, which his wife [[Kim Kardashian]] was not aware of until she heard about West's announcement through social media,<ref name=\"KUWTKs16e2\"/> and that he was actively working on a collaborative studio album with Chance the Rapper titled ''Good Ass Job''.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8475336/kanye-west-rhymefest-chicago-chance-the-rapper-new-music|title=Kanye West Shares Videos Featuring Rhymefest, Chance The Rapper and Music Snippets in Chicago: Watch|date=September 16, 2018|accessdate=September 19, 2018|first=Bonnie|last=Stiernberg|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920112350/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8475336/kanye-west-rhymefest-chicago-chance-the-rapper-new-music|archive-date=September 20, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> West ultimately didn't move back to Chicago and ''Good Ass Job'' has yet to materialize.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/2019/9/17/20868743/kanye-west-chicago-avalon-regal-art-institute-yeezy|title=It's been a year since Kanye West promised to move back to Chicago. So where is he?|work=Chicago Sun-Times|date=September 17, 2019|accessdate=December 8, 2019|first=Alice|last=Bazerghi|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190918035834/https://chicago.suntimes.com/2019/9/17/20868743/kanye-west-chicago-avalon-regal-art-institute-yeezy|archive-date=September 18, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8478628/chance-the-rapper-good-ass-job-kanye-west-hasnt-started|title=Chance The Rapper Says 'Good Ass Job' Project With Kanye West 'Hasn't Started Yet'|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|first=Michael|last=Saponara|date=October 8, 2018|accessdate=September 19, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181009121432/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8478628/chance-the-rapper-good-ass-job-kanye-west-hasnt-started|archive-date=October 9, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Yandhi Cover Art (Free License).jpg|thumb|right|alt=Full quality cover art for Kanye West's ninth studio album ''Yandhi''|The cover art for ''Yandhi'' revealed in September 2018. The minimalist recordable [[MiniDisc]] with a purple shutter was compared to the cover art of West's sixth studio album ''[[Yeezus]]'' (2013), with speculation that ''Yandhi'' would've been a follow-up album.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/kanye-west-teases-new-album-yandhi-dropping-this-month-news.60011.html|title=Kanye West Teases New Album \"Yandhi\" Dropping This Month|first=Kevin|last=Goddard|work=HotNewHipHop|date=September 18, 2018|accessdate=September 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180918114121/https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/kanye-west-teases-new-album-yandhi-dropping-this-month-news.60011.html|archive-date=September 18, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2018/09/kanye-west-might-be-teasing-yeezus-follow-up-album|title=Kanye Announces Release Date for 'Yeezus' Follow-Up 'Yandhi'|magazine=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|first=Abel|last=Shifferaw|date=September 17, 2018|accessdate=September 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180918111332/https://www.complex.com/music/2018/09/kanye-west-might-be-teasing-yeezus-follow-up-album|archive-date=September 18, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>]]\nOn September 17, 2018, West announced his ninth studio album ''Yandhi'', just three months after the release of his previous solo album ''Ye'', revealing the cover art and initial release date of September 29, 2018.<ref name=\"Reveal\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.thefader.com/2018/09/18/kanye-west-new-project-yandhi-announcement|title=Kanye West announces new project ''Yandhi''|date=September 18, 2018|accessdate=March 11, 2019|magazine=The Fader|first=Salvator|last=Maicki|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190227144745/http://www.thefader.com/2018/09/18/kanye-west-new-project-yandhi-announcement|archive-date=February 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On September 27, 2018, West visited ''[[The Fader]]'' headquarters to preview new music from ''Yandhi'' and invited people to change up the lyrics. Songs previewed included vocals from [[Ty Dolla Sign]], 6ix9ine, and posthumous vocals from [[XXXTentacion]]; West was awaiting [[Rihanna]] to send in vocals for a track.<ref name=\"FADER\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2018/09/27/kanye-west-fader-maga-hat-kaepernick|title=Here's what happened during Kanye West's visit to The Fader|website=The Fader|date=September 27, 2018|accessdate=April 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402221719/https://www.thefader.com/2018/09/27/kanye-west-fader-maga-hat-kaepernick|archive-date=April 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> A working track list for the initial version of ''Yandhi'' included \"I Love It\" with Lil Pump, \"[[We Got Love (Teyana Taylor song)|We Got Love]]\" with Teyana Taylor and [[Lauryn Hill]] (originally intended for ''K.T.S.E.''),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/teyana-taylors-we-got-love-leaks-with-vocals-from-lauryn-hill-news.54777.html|title=Teyana Taylor's \"We Got Love\" Leaks With Vocals From Lauryn Hill|date=June 11, 2018|accessdate=September 18, 2019|website=HotNewHipHop|first=Alex|last=Zidel|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191026120450/https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/teyana-taylors-we-got-love-leaks-with-vocals-from-lauryn-hill-news.54777.html|archive-date=October 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>{{efn|Teyana Taylor later released \"We Got Love\" as a single in December 2019, with it including production from West.<ref name=\"WeGotLove\">{{Cite web|last1=Darville|first1=Jordan|url=https://www.thefader.com/2019/12/06/teyana-taylor-we-got-love-kanye-west|title=Teyana Taylor shares Kanye West-produced \"We Got Love\"|date=December 6, 2019|accessdate=December 8, 2019|website=The Fader}}</ref>}} and \"[[New Body]]\", which [[Nicki Minaj]] recorded her verse for in under an hour after Kardashian coordinated to get her featured on the song.<ref name=\"Verse\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/kanye-west-nicki-minaj-collab/|title=Kanye West & Nicki Minaj Tease \"Dope\" Collab Track \"New Body\"|date=April 8, 2019|accessdate=December 20, 2019|work=[[Highsnobiety]]|author=Snowden, Heather}}</ref><ref name=\"KUWTKs16e2\">{{Cite episode|title=Kourtney's Choice|series=[[Keeping Up with the Kardashians]]|season=16|number=2|date=April 7, 2019}}</ref> Other tracks included \"The Storm\", \"Bye Bye Baby\", \"Hurricane\", \"Alien / SpaceX\", \"Last Name\", \"City in the Sky / Garden\", and \"Chakras\".<ref name=\"KUWTKs16e2\"/>\n\n[[File:Morning in Murchison Falls National Park.JPG|thumb|left|alt=Morning on Nile in Murchison falls National Park|West recorded at the [[Murchison Falls National Park]], [[Uganda]] in October 2018]]\nWest was the musical guest for the [[Saturday Night Live (season 44)|season 44 premiere]] of ''[[Saturday Night Live|Saturday Night Live (SNL)]]'', slated to coincide with the release of ''Yandhi'' on September 29, 2018.<ref name=\"snl\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/kanye-to-perform-on-snl/|title=Kanye to Perform on \"SNL\"|last1=Sodomsky|last2=Minsker|first1=Sam|first2=Evan|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=September 18, 2018|accessdate=September 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180918114538/https://pitchfork.com/news/kanye-to-perform-on-snl/|archive-date=September 18, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Universal Music Publishing Group]] accidentally leaked that the initial version of the album was to be eight tracks long that same month, with Clemons being shown to have contributed to seven of the tracks.<ref name=\"Eight\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2018/09/kanyes-yandhi-8-tracks-long|title=Kanye West's 'Yandhi' May Be 8 Tracks Long|magazine=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|date=September 30, 2018|accessdate=October 22, 2018|first=Joe|last=Price|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181022232549/https://www.complex.com/music/2018/09/kanyes-yandhi-8-tracks-long|archive-date=October 22, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> After the album went unreleased, a rescheduled date of November 23, 2018 was announced by Kardashian on October 1 of that year.<ref name=\"kimreveal\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8477725/kanye-west-yandhi-album-pushed-back-black-friday|last=Lamarre|first=Carl|title=Kim Kardashian-West Says Kanye's 'Yandhi' Album Will Now Drop Nov. 23: 'Trust Me, It's Worth the Wait'|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=October 1, 2018|accessdate=September 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190921012651/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8477725/kanye-west-yandhi-album-pushed-back-black-friday|archive-date=September 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> That same day, West visited the [[TMZ]] offices for an interview, admitting that the album wasn't actually finished yet and that he would be going to Africa in two weeks to continue recording for ''Yandhi''. West talked about recording in Chicago and how he \"felt the roots\" but wanted to go to further his energy by touching African soil and recording in nature.<ref name=\"TMZ\"/> West said the previous five albums he released in 2018 as the Wyoming Sessions were \"superhero rehabilitation\" and declared that ''Yandhi'' was a \"full Ye album,\" with West comparing it to his critically acclaimed albums ''[[808s & Heartbreak]]'' (2008), ''[[My Beautiful Dark Twisted Fantasy]]'' (2010), and ''[[Watch the Throne]]'' (2011), the latter of which is a collaboration with fellow rapper [[Jay-Z]]. West stated that \"the alien Ye is like, fully back in mode, off of medication.\"<ref name=\"TMZ\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.tmz.com/2018/10/01/kanye-west-yandhi-album-delayed-africa-black-friday-release/|title=Kanye West's 'Yandhi' Album Release Pushed Back, Recording in Africa|date=October 1, 2018|publisher=[[TMZ]]|accessdate=October 1, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181002004207/http://www.tmz.com/2018/10/01/kanye-west-yandhi-album-delayed-africa-black-friday-release/|archive-date=October 2, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn October 12, 2018, West arrived in [[Uganda]] and restarted work on the album in a dome-shaped studio set up in the Chobe Safari Lodge at the [[Murchison Falls National Park]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://qz.com/africa/1424230/kanye-west-kim-kardashian-west-in-uganda-to-finish-yandhi-album/|title=Kanye West has built a studio in a Ugandan safari lodge to finish his album|first=Lynsey|last=Shutel|date=October 15, 2018|accessdate=January 30, 2019|website=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190131040546/https://qz.com/africa/1424230/kanye-west-kim-kardashian-west-in-uganda-to-finish-yandhi-album/|archive-date=January 31, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> West played new music, including a studio recording of the \"We Got Love\" remix, for a group of about 100 Ugandan school children during a charity event.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8480280/kanye-west-uganda-yeezys|title=Kanye West Visits Orphanage in Uganda, Gifts Hundreds of Kids With Yeezy Sneakers|date=October 16, 2018|accessdate=January 30, 2019|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|first=Michael|last=Saponara|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190131053342/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8480280/kanye-west-uganda-yeezys|archive-date=January 31, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In an October 21, 2018 interview, [[Quavo]] stated that his trio [[Migos]] had recorded for the album.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/quavo-confirms-that-migos-will-feature-on-kanye-wests-yandhi-news.62712.html|title=Quavo Confirms That Migos Will Feature On Kanye West's \"Yandhi\"|date=October 21, 2018|accessdate=October 21, 2018|website=HotNewHipHop|first=Devin|last=Ch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181021215054/https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/quavo-confirms-that-migos-will-feature-on-kanye-wests-yandhi-news.62712.html|archive-date=October 21, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In November 2018, following a Kids See Ghosts performance with Kid Cudi at [[Tyler, the Creator]]'s [[Camp Flog Gnaw Carnival]], West tweeted that he felt ''Yandhi'' was not finished, and that he would \"announce the release date once it's done,\" delaying the album indefinitely.<ref name=\"NovDelay\">{{cite web|first=Alex|last=Young|title=Kanye delays release of Yandhi again |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2018/11/kanye-delays-release-of-yandhi-again/ |work=[[Consequence of Sound]]|accessdate=April 5, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190323124006/https://consequenceofsound.net/2018/11/kanye-delays-release-of-yandhi-again/ |archivedate=March 23, 2019 |date=November 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===December 2018 \u2013 April 2019: Miami and the Sunday Service Choir===\n{{See also|Sunday Service Choir}}\n[[File:Timbaland1292010.jpg|thumb|left|200px|American record producer [[Timbaland]] began working on the album in December 2018 and contributed production on five tracks.]]\nIn December 2018, West reiterated on Twitter that he was still not taking medications for his bipolar disorder in order to record music on the same level as some of his previous works.<ref name=\"atlantic\"/> Amanda Mull, writing for ''[[The Atlantic]]'', described West's erratic tweets as promoting \"a dangerous myth\" that suffering is required for great art and creativity.<ref name=\"atlantic\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2018/12/kanye-west-and-dangers-quitting-psychiatric-medication/578647/|title=Kanye West and the Dangers of Going off Psychiatric Meds|website=[[The Atlantic]]|author=Mull, Amanda|date=20 December 2018|accessdate=5 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190517024918/https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2018/12/kanye-west-and-dangers-quitting-psychiatric-medication/578647/|archive-date=May 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> That same month, American record producer [[Timbaland]] and Argentinian jazz pianist Federico Vindver were recording in [[Miami]] when West joined their studio session to make \"more healing music\" for ''Yandhi''.<ref name=\"Vindver\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/kanye-west-coldplay-federico-vindver-producer-924043/|title=How an Argentinean Jazz Pianist Became Kanye West and Coldplay's Go-To Producer|author=Leight, Elia|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=10 December 2019|accessdate=14 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191212040502/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/kanye-west-coldplay-federico-vindver-producer-924043/|archive-date=December 12, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Clemons was also invited to a record in Miami after he had been talked about to Timbaland by West \"nonstop.\"<ref name=\"Ant\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/10/ant-clemons-interview-kanye-west-jesus-is-king-collaborator|title=Ant Clemons Shares Stories Behind Kanye West's 'Jesus Is King' Songs and His Solo Single|last1=McKinney|first1=Jessica|website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|accessdate=January 16, 2019|date=October 29, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191030131653/https://www.complex.com/music/2019/10/ant-clemons-interview-kanye-west-jesus-is-king-collaborator|archive-date=October 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In January 2019, West began splitting time between [[Los Angeles]] and his newly purchased house in Miami, being seen in the latter city with Timbaland recording with other artists such as [[Lil Wayne]], [[2 Chainz]], Migos, [[Tee Grizzley]], and [[YNW Melly]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tmz.com/2019/01/07/kanye-west-new-album-lil-wayne-migos-timbaland-2chainz/|title=Kanye West Working on New Album in Miami with Guests Lil Wayne, Migos and Timbaland|publisher=TMZ|date=January 7, 2019|access-date=January 30, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190131044151/https://www.tmz.com/2019/01/07/kanye-west-new-album-lil-wayne-migos-timbaland-2chainz/|archive-date=January 31, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn the first Sunday of 2019, West began the first rehearsal for the [[Sunday Service Choir]], where he performed [[Gospel music|gospel]] arrangements of songs from his discography and other songs with choir group The Samples,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://getuperica.com/116782/kanye-wests-sunday-service-choir-director-jason-white-his-wife-geneen-give-insight-on-the-series-exclusive-video/|title=Kanye West's \"Sunday Service\" Choir Director Jason White & His Wife Geneen Give Insight On The Series|first=Aliya|last=Faust|date=April 2, 2019|accessdate=April 19, 2019|website=Get Up! Mornings with Erica Campbell|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406014430/https://getuperica.com/116782/kanye-wests-sunday-service-choir-director-jason-white-his-wife-geneen-give-insight-on-the-series-exclusive-video/|archive-date=April 6, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and frequent collaborators such as [[The World Famous Tony Williams|Tony Williams]] and Clemons. Guest performers have included [[Francis and the Lights]], Kid Cudi, and 070 Shake.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2019/01/kanye-west-sunday-service-gospel-video/|title=Kanye West leads Sunday Service featuring gospel versions of his songs: Watch|magazine=[[Consequence of Sound]]|date=January 7, 2019|accessdate=March 4, 2019|first=Lake|last=Schatz|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190202041845/https://consequenceofsound.net/2019/01/kanye-west-sunday-service-gospel-video/|archive-date=February 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On February 14, 2019, West met saxophonist [[Kenny G]] for the first time after hiring him for a [[Valentine's Day]] performance. The day after, West began previewing new songs to him in the studio and Kenny G suggested that his saxophone \"would sound really good\" on \"[[Use This Gospel]]\". West pulled out a microphone and Kenny G recorded his part, keeping the track for later reverb and EQ tweaks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gq.com/story/kenny-g-interview-jesus-is-king|title=Kenny G Explains How He (Probably) Made It Onto Kanye West's New Album|first=Max|last=Cea|date=October 8, 2019|accessdate=October 8, 2019|work=[[GQ]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191008223812/https://www.gq.com/story/kenny-g-interview-jesus-is-king|archive-date=October 8, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{external media\n| float = right\n| width  = 280px\n| video1 = [https://twitter.com/CyhiThePrynce/status/1099787255101550593 \"This the only time we allow dope on Sundays\"] \u2013 Viral Twitter video showing West lead the outdoor Sunday Service Choir rehearsal.}}\nOn February 25, 2019, Sunday Service was rehearsed outdoors for the first time. A video of West playing a keyboard and leading a group of musicians and singers in recording a cover of [[Fred Hammond]]'s \"[[Free to Worship|This Is The Day]]\" was tweeted by rapper [[Cyhi the Prynce]] and went viral.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8499827/kanye-west-leads-another-sunday-service|title=Kanye West Leads Another Edition Of Sunday Service|date=February 25, 2019|accessdate=March 4, 2019|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|first=Michael|last=Saponara|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302172417/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8499827/kanye-west-leads-another-sunday-service|archive-date=March 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Timbaland shared a snippet of a ''Yandhi'' track on Instagram in March 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/timbaland-teases-brief-kanye-west-yandhi-snippet-news.74348.html|title=Timbaland Teases Brief Kanye West \"Yandhi\" Snippet|website=HotNewHipHop|last1=Findlay|first1=Mitch|date=March 13, 2019|accessdate=January 16, 2019}}</ref> The track \"[[Water (Kanye West song)|Water]]\" had been recorded in April 2019,<ref name=\"Ant\"/> and was debuted live less than a week later with Clemons and Ty Dolla Sign at the first public Sunday Service Choir performance, at [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival|Coachella]] for [[Easter]] on April 21, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/19/entertainment/kanye-sunday-service-coachella/index.html|title=Kanye's Sunday Service is coming to Coachella, but what is it?|date=April 19, 2019|accessdate=April 19, 2019|publisher=[[CNN]]|author=France, Lisa Repers|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190419173907/https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/19/entertainment/kanye-sunday-service-coachella/index.html|archive-date=April 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Water\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/watch-kanye-west-debut-new-song-water-coachella-sunday-service-2479259|title=Watch Kanye West debut new song 'Water' at Coachella Sunday Service|date=April 21, 2019|accessdate=April 21, 2019|work=[[NME]]|first=Rhian|last=Daly|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190421185706/https://www.nme.com/news/music/watch-kanye-west-debut-new-song-water-coachella-sunday-service-2479259|archive-date=April 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In April 2019, West has claimed that he was \"radically saved\" around the time of the Coachella performance and later enlisted Adam Tyson as a personal [[pastor]] for weekly [[Bible study (Christianity)|Bible studies]].<ref name=\"Tyson\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2019/10/09/kanye-west-pastor-wrote-jesus-is-king-says-kanye-was-radically-saved-2019|title=Kanye West's pastor worked on Jesus Is King, says Kanye was \"radically saved\"|first=Shaad|last=D'Souza|date=October 9, 2019|accessdate=October 13, 2019|work=The Fader|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191012044122/https://www.thefader.com/2019/10/09/kanye-west-pastor-wrote-jesus-is-king-says-kanye-was-radically-saved-2019|archive-date=October 12, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===May \u2013 October 2019: Wyoming and ''Jesus Is King''===\n[[File:Cedar Mountain - panoramio (1).jpg|thumb|right|alt=Cedar Mountain|In September 2019, West returned to [[Wyoming]] to finish ''Jesus Is King'', the same state where he recorded his previous solo album ''[[Ye (album)|Ye]]'' (2018).]]\nIn May 2019, West invited American rappers Pusha T and [[No Malice]] to [[Wyoming]],<ref name=\"vulture\"/> the same state where West recorded his previous two albums ''Ye'' and ''Kids See Ghosts''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-blogs/kanye-wyoming-albums-ultimate-playlist-2346377|title=Kanye and company's 'Wyoming albums' \u2013 the ultimate, brutally edited, best-of playlist|date=June 29, 2018|accessdate=September 22, 2019|work=NME|first=Luke Morgan|last=Britton|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190808081937/https://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-blogs/kanye-wyoming-albums-ultimate-playlist-2346377|archive-date=August 8, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Pusha T and No Malice reunited as their duo [[Clipse]]. A feature from Clipse was requested by West, though Pusha T had been unsure about whether or not No Malice would say yes. Their feature on \"Use This Gospel\" marked the first time in five years since No Malice stated that the duo would never perform together again. West no longer wanted to rap on the album until he was persuaded by No Malice.<ref name=\"vulture\">{{cite web |last1=Harris |first1=Hunter |url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/10/pusha-t-interview-clipse-reunion-kanye-jesus-is-king.html |title=Pusha T on Reunting Clipse for Kanye's 'Jesus Is King' |publisher=[[Vulture.com|Vulture]] |date=October 25, 2019 |accessdate=November 13, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191025174358/https://www.vulture.com/2019/10/pusha-t-interview-clipse-reunion-kanye-jesus-is-king.html |archive-date=October 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> West also spoke to Tyson about quitting rapping because he viewed it as \"the devil's music,\" to which Tyson suggested that West rap for God.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2019/10/21/kanye-west-quit-rap-devils-music|title=Kanye West almost quit rap and called it \"the devil's music,\" according to his pastor|date=October 21, 2019|accessdate=December 20, 2019|work=[[The Fader]]|author=Darville, Jordan|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191221015149/https://www.thefader.com/2019/10/21/kanye-west-quit-rap-devils-music|archive-date=December 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Tyson was invited to weigh in on how to include [[Christian music|Christian]] elements within the album.<ref name=\"Tyson\"/>\n\nIn the summer, Vindver was invited to Wyoming and [[Calabasas, California]] to work on the project again, where he produced the track \"[[Hands On (song)|Hands On]]\". Vindver noted that West's \"faith went past a point of no return.\"<ref name=\"Vindver\"/> In July 2019, the planned release of the standalone promotional single \"[[Brothers (Kanye West song)|Brothers]]\" was abruptly cancelled due to a shift in focus on ''Yandhi''.<ref name=\"Forbes\">{{cite web|last1=Lambert|first1=Chris|title=What Happened To \"Brothers,\" The Kanye West Song That Vanished?|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/chrislambert/2019/08/07/what-happened-to-brothers-the-kanye-west-song-that-vanished/amp/|website=Forbes|accessdate=21 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190808164443/https://www.forbes.com/sites/chrislambert/2019/08/07/what-happened-to-brothers-the-kanye-west-song-that-vanished/amp/|archive-date=August 8, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> That same month, Nicki Minaj stated during an episode of ''[[Queen Radio]]'' that West had recently made her aware of him being a [[Born again|born-again Christian]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8525727/nicki-minaj-kanye-west-born-again-christian|title=Nicki Minaj Says Kanye West Told Her He's a 'Born-Again Christian': 'I Could See There's a Peace He Has Now'|date=August 1, 2019|accessdate=August 30, 2019|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|first=Michael|last=Saponara|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190830140946/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8525727/nicki-minaj-kanye-west-born-again-christian|archive-date=August 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> West quit his self-diagnosed [[pornography addiction]] and asked collaborators on the album not to engage in [[premarital sex]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/25/entertainment/kanye-west-premarital-sex-trnd/index.html|title=Kanye West asked his collaborators not to have premarital sex|author=France, Lisa Respers|date=October 25, 2019|accessdate=December 20, 2019|publisher=CNN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230003811/https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/25/entertainment/kanye-west-premarital-sex-trnd/index.html|archive-date=December 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn August 29, 2019, Kardashian announced ''Jesus Is King'' by posting a handwritten tracklist of the project on her [[Twitter]]. The note also listed a September 27, 2019 release date.<ref name=\"JIK\">{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/new-kanye-west-album-jesus-is-king-878415/|title=Kim Kardashian Teases Track List for New Kanye West Album 'Jesus Is King'|work=Rolling Stone|first=Charles|last=Holmes|date=August 29, 2019|accessdate=September 12, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914093002/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/new-kanye-west-album-jesus-is-king-878415/|archive-date=September 14, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In early September 2019, West was reportedly finishing up the album with Pusha T at his newly purchased ranch in [[Cody, Wyoming]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/09/kanye-west-purchases-14-million-dollar-ranch-wyoming|title=Kanye West Purchases Enormous $14 Million Ranch in Wyoming|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|first=Tara|last=Mahadevan|date=September 6, 2019|accessdate=September 22, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190921184603/https://www.complex.com/music/2019/09/kanye-west-purchases-14-million-dollar-ranch-wyoming|archive-date=September 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On September 25, 2019, multiple sources indicated that [[Def Jam Recordings|Def Jam]] executives had met with West in Wyoming and that the album would miss its scheduled released date.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/music/news/kanye-west-new-album-not-coming-friday-kim-kardashian-disagrees-jesus-is-king-1203348966/|title=Kanye West's New Album Is Not Coming Friday, Source Says \u2013 But Kim Kardashian Disagrees?|author=Aswad, Jen|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=September 25, 2019|accessdate=December 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8531383/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-delay|title=Kanye West Delays 'Jesus Is King' Release|date=September 25, 2019|accessdate=December 20, 2019|author=Saponara, Michael|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219221747/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8531383/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-delay|archive-date=December 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Following a listening party in [[Detroit]], Kardashian announced that the album would miss its September 27 release date and would instead be released two days later on September 29, 2019, as mixing had to be finalized.<ref name=\"Mixing\"/> Within the two days, West had re-recorded the track \"Selah\" and was still awaiting a new Nicki Minaj verse for \"New Body\".{{efn|\"New Body\" initially leaked online in July 2019.<ref name=\"LeakNewBody01\"/> It was revealed in October 2019 by the latter that she was re-recording her verse to be religious, but that her and West were having disagreements.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bet.com/music/2019/10/24/nicki-minaj-kanye-west-new-body.html|title=Nicki Minaj Says Kanye West Wants to Turn 'New Body' Collab Into Gospel Song|date=24 October 2019|accessdate=14 December 2019|publisher=[[BET]]|author=Reese, Alexis|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214182254/https://www.bet.com/music/2019/10/24/nicki-minaj-kanye-west-new-body.html|archive-date=December 14, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The track was ultimately scrapped from the album.}} The September 29 release date was also missed.<ref name=\"NewYork\"/> According to TMZ, the album had already been completed, but West was continually revising it since he was unsatisfied with the end product.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/09/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-delayed|title=Kanye West's 'Jesus Is King' Has Reportedly Been Delayed Again|date=September 30, 2019|accessdate=October 1, 2019|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|first=Joe|last=Price|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191001115831/https://www.complex.com/music/2019/09/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-delayed|archive-date=October 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In October 2019, West continued working on the album in Wyoming and invited [[Swizz Beatz]] to help finish it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/kanye-west-swizz-beats-wyoming/|title=Kanye West & Swizz Beatz Are in \"Album Mode\" in Wyoming|date=October 11, 2019|first=Feleg|last=Tesema|work=[[Highsnobiety]]|accessdate=October 15, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191014002144/https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/kanye-west-swizz-beats-wyoming/|archive-date=October 14, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn October 21, West tweeted out a new release date, October 25, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/10/new-kanye-album-jesus-is-king-will-allegedly-drop-october-25.html|title=New Kanye album Jesus Is King will allegedly drop October 25|publisher=Vulture|date=October 21, 2019|first=Halle|last=Kiefer|accessdate=October 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191026120450/https://www.vulture.com/2019/10/new-kanye-album-jesus-is-king-will-allegedly-drop-october-25.html|archive-date=October 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> West cut the songs \"New Body\", \"[[Up from the Ashes (song)|Up from the Ashes]]\", and \"[[LA Monster]]\" from the album.<ref name=\"Grapple\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/can-kanye-west-save-gospel-choirs-893633/|title=Can Kanye West Save Gospel Choirs?|last1=Leight|first1=Elias|website=Rolling Stone|date=October 25, 2019|accessdate=April 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207171352/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/can-kanye-west-save-gospel-choirs-893633/|archive-date=February 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"P4k2\">{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/kanye-west-shares-official-jesus-is-king-tracklist/|title=Kanye West Shares Official ''Jesus Is King'' Tracklist|date=October 24, 2019|accessdate=April 2, 2020|work=Pitchfork|last1=Strauss|first1=Matthew}}</ref> ''Jesus Is King'' went on to miss its midnight premiere, with West explaining the delay hours after by tweeting: \"To my fans, Thank you for being loyal & patient. We are specifically fixing mixes on 'Everything We Need' '[[Follow God]]' & 'Water'.\"<ref name=\"newsweek\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/kanye-west-jesus-king-release-date-time-delayed-twitter-1467676|title=Kanye West Delays New Album 'Jesus Is King' again and Twitter is not happy|work=[[Newsweek]]|first=Samuel|last=Spencer|date=October 25, 2019|access-date=October 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191025171944/https://www.newsweek.com/kanye-west-jesus-king-release-date-time-delayed-twitter-1467676|archive-date=October 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> West entrusted frequent collaborator [[Consequence (rapper)|Consequence]] to overlook final mixing and the album was delivered to streaming services at 4:30 AM.<ref name=\"Cons\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/12/consequence-interview-complexcon-kanye-west-jesus-is-king|title=Consequence Drops \"ComplexCon\" Video, Talks Last-Minute Sprint to Finish Kanye's 'Jesus Is King'|author=McKinney, Jessica|date=5 December 2019|accessdate=5 December 2019|website=Complex}}</ref> ''Jesus Is King'' was ultimately released on its planned release date.<ref name=\"Film\">{{cite news |last=Leight |first=Elias |title=Kanye West Releases 'Jesus Is King,' Capping Hectic Rollout Saga |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-album-892092/ |work=Rolling Stone |date=October 25, 2019 |accessdate=October 25, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191025162934/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-album-892092/ |archive-date=October 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Music and production==\n{{Listen\n|filename= Kanye West - Selah.ogg\n|pos= right\n|title= \"Selah\"\n|description=Sample of the album's second track \"[[Selah (Kanye West song)|Selah]]\", which is the first full track on the album and includes West rapping over organ chords.<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/><ref name=\"O'connor\"/><ref name=\"Nguyen\"/> The [[Refrain|chorus]] is a rendition of [[Gospel music|gospel]] song \"Revelation 9:1\", as performed by the [[Sunday Service Choir]].<ref name=\"Selah\">{{Cite web|last1=Zidel|first1=Alex|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/kanye-wests-sunday-service-choir-returns-with-hallelujah-filled-revelations-19-1-new-song.1985628.html|title=Kanye West's Sunday Service Choir Returns With Hallelujah-Filled \"Revelations 19:1\"|date=December 27, 2019|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=April 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403105345/https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/kanye-wests-sunday-service-choir-returns-with-hallelujah-filled-revelations-19-1-new-song.1985628.html|archive-date=April 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>}}\n''Jesus Is King'' is a [[Christian hip hop]] record, and features a significant gospel influence.<ref name=\"rs-wip\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/kanye-wests-jesus-is-king-a-work-in-progress-892567/|title=Kanye West's 'Jesus Is King' Still Sounds Like a Work-in-Progress|work=Rolling Stone|date=September 30, 2019|accessdate=October 2, 2019|first=Charles|last=Holmes|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191001125147/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/kanye-wests-jesus-is-king-a-work-in-progress-892567/|archive-date=October 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"rs-detroit\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-live-reviews/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-detroit-892196/|title=Inside Kanye West's Album (and Film) Premiere in Detroit|work=Rolling Stone|date=September 28, 2019|accessdate=October 2, 2019|first=Samuel J.|last=Robinson|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191001024556/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-live-reviews/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-detroit-892196/|archive-date=October 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'' journalist Eric Skelton considered that it was not a sonic departure from West's previous work, noting its \"healthy doses of bass, pretty chords, [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] sensibilities, and [[Pop music|pop]] melodies.\" and claimed that it borrows  elements from his past albums such as ''My Beautiful Dark Twisted Fantasy'', ''Ye'', and ''[[The Life of Pablo]]'' (2016),<ref name=\"complex-ny\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/09/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-experience-new-york-city|title='Can I Bring the Gospel to New York Real Quick?': Experiencing Kanye West's Sunday in NYC|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|date=September 30, 2019|accessdate=October 2, 2019|first=Eric|last=Skelton|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191001115849/https://www.complex.com/music/2019/09/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-experience-new-york-city|archive-date=October 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> while Samuel J. Robinson of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' highlighted its use of [[Trap music|trap]] drums, [[ambient music|ambient]] flourishes and [[Sampling (music)|samples]].<ref name=\"rs-detroit\"/> However, Charles Holmes, also from ''Rolling Stone'', described it as a \"far more muted, stripped-down affair than most West albums,\" with him noting the exception of the track \"[[On God (Kanye West song)|On God]]\", produced by [[Pi'erre Bourne]], due to its \"galactic, fiery, and intense\" beat.<ref name=\"rs-wip\"/>\n\nHolmes also considered that, despite its gospel influences, \"''Jesus Is King'' is a gospel album in the same way a square is a rectangle,\" only fitting \"the most basic criteria,\" and wrote that its production consists largely of recognizable gospel components such as \"pared-back guitars, mournful organs and pianos, and choral arrangements deployed like [[Soul music|soul]] samples.\"<ref name=\"rs-wip\"/> [[Andrew Legg]], Tasmanian musician and director of the [[ARIA Music Awards|ARIA award]]-nominated [[Southern Gospel Choir]] described ''Jesus is King'' as \"a remarkable gospel album,\" calling it contemporary in a genuine way and he predicted that the album would \"inevitably challenge the traditional concept of [[African Americans|African American]] gospel while influencing it shape for years to come.\"<ref name=\"LeggGospel\">{{cite web |last1=Legg |first1=Andrew |title=I teach and play gospel music and I think Kanye's Jesus is King is a remarkable gospel album |url=https://theconversation.com/i-teach-and-play-gospel-music-and-i-think-kanyes-jesus-is-king-is-a-remarkable-gospel-album-126191 |website=The Conversation |accessdate=November 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191109160039/https://theconversation.com/i-teach-and-play-gospel-music-and-i-think-kanyes-jesus-is-king-is-a-remarkable-gospel-album-126191 |archive-date=November 9, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Writing for ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', [[Neil McCormick]] viewed ''Jesus Is King'' as where \"West has confounded expectations once again with a set of dramatic, evangelical hip hop testimonials.\"<ref name=\"Tele\"/> McCormick commented that choir elements of gospel are included on it, while also citing church organs, [[Synthesizer|synths]] and [[vocoder]] harmonies as being present.<ref name=\"Tele\"/> Torsten Ingvaldsen from ''Hypebeast'' noted the influence taken from West's previous albums, describing ''Jesus Is King'' as what \"can be seen as Kanye's way of reenvisioning his past, updating it within his own hip-hop missionary lens in an attempt to bring something new to these seemingly anachronistic principles.\"<ref>{{Cite web|first=Torsten|last=Ingvaldsen|url=https://hypebeast.com/2019/11/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-album-review|title=Kanye West 'Jesus Is King' Album Review|work=Hypebeast|date=November 1, 2019|accessdate=November 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191105004155/https://hypebeast.com/2019/11/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-album-review|archive-date=November 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Themes and lyrics==\n[[File:President Donald Trump and Kanye West 2018-10-11 (Cropped 2).jpg|thumb|right|alt=[[Donald Trump]] and Kanye West meeting in October 2018|West references the [[Thirteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Thirteenth Amendment]] on \"[[On God (Kanye West song)|On God]]\" and \"[[Hands On (song)|Hands On]]\". In October 2018, West met with US president [[Donald Trump]] and discussed altering the amendment.<ref name=\"Trump\"/>]]\n''Jesus Is King'' focuses on the [[Christianity|Christian]] concept of [[salvation in Christianity|salvation]]. Keeping with its Christian theme, the album's lyrics do not contain any [[profanity]] or sexual references, including those performed by guest vocalists. West spoke at the listening party in New York on September 29, 2019, stating: \"This album has been made to be an expression of [[the gospel]] and to share the gospel and the truth of what Jesus has done to me. When I think of the goodness of Jesus and all that he does for me, my soul cries out.\"<ref name=\"NewYork\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/30/arts/music/kanye-west-jesus-is-king.html|title=Kanye West Teases 'Jesus Is King,' a New Album With No Cursing|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=September 30, 2019|accessdate=October 1, 2019|first=Joe|last=Coscarelli|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191001010128/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/30/arts/music/kanye-west-jesus-is-king.html|archive-date=October 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Tyson was present in the studio for the recording of ''Jesus Is King'' and helped tweak certain lyrics \"to articulate the gospel more clearly\" despite claiming that the work is all West's and Tyson didn't view himself as writing any of the songs.<ref name=\"Tyson\"/> This was claimed by Tyson to be part of the creative process of him and West.<ref name=\"Tyson\"/> The album also focused on [[sanctification]]\u2014obeying Jesus, avoiding [[Christian views on sin|sin]], and growing in one's faith.<ref name=\"Silberman2019\">{{cite web |last1=James |first1=Silberman |title=10 Best Lines From Kanye West's New Album 'Jesus Is King' |url=https://thefederalist.com/2019/10/28/10-best-lines-from-kanye-wests-new-album-jesus-is-king/ |website=[[The Federalist (website)|The Federalist]] |accessdate=October 30, 2019 |date=October 28, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191029143318/https://thefederalist.com/2019/10/28/10-best-lines-from-kanye-wests-new-album-jesus-is-king/ |archive-date=October 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Indeed, West \"asked people working on the album to fast or to avoid premarital sex.\"<ref name=\"Graham2019\">{{cite web|last1=Graham|first1=Ruth|title=Evangelicals Are Extremely Excited About Kanye's Jesus Is King|url=https://slate.com/human-interest/2019/10/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-evangelical-biblical.html|work=[[Slate Magazine]]|accessdate=October 30, 2019|date=October 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191029162030/https://slate.com/human-interest/2019/10/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-evangelical-biblical.html|archive-date=October 29, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In the song \"Hands On\", West asks fellow Christians to [[Christian prayer|pray]] for him so \"that he may learn and grow in sanctification.\"<ref name=\"Silberman2019\"/> Tyson had discussed both [[Justification (theology)|justification]] and sanctification with West in their conversation.<ref name=\"Bettis2019\">{{cite web |last1=Bettis |first1=Karra |title=Master's Seminary Grad Takes Kanye's Crowds to Church |url=https://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2019/october-web-only/masters-seminary-grad-takes-kanyes-crowds-to-church.html |work=[[Christianity Today]] |accessdate=October 30, 2019 |date=October 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191012075855/https://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2019/october-web-only/masters-seminary-grad-takes-kanyes-crowds-to-church.html |archive-date=October 12, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{{Listen\n|filename= Kanye West - Follow God.ogg\n|pos= left\n|title= \"Follow God\"\n|description=Sample of the lead single from the album, \"[[Follow God]]\", which contains [[Sampling (music)|samples]] of the recording \"Can You Lose By Following God\", performed by Whole Truth.<ref name=\"rhythmic\"/><ref name=\"mainstream\"/><ref name=\"sample\"/> The song sees West fighting against his failures linked to [[Christianity]] as well as the troubled relationship between him and his real father, the latter of which leads to West considering the meaning of being \"Christlike\" due to two of them having an argument.<ref name=\"cos\"/><ref name=\"Kameir\"/>}}\nWest emphasized that the purpose of ''Jesus Is King'' was to preach the gospel and [[evangelism|evangelize]], leading to nonbelievers' [[conversion to Christianity]].<ref name=\"Silberman2019\"/> This was made clear in the song \"God Is\", where West sings \"Everybody, I will tell 'til the whole world is healed.\"<ref name=\"Silberman2019\"/> Within the album's opening track \"[[Every Hour]]\", the Sunday Service Choir implores people to \"sing until the power of the Lord comes down.\"<ref name=\"Bassett\"/> \"Selah\", the first full track on ''Jesus Is King'', sees West assert his faith.<ref name=\"O'connor\"/><ref name=\"Nguyen\"/> It includes West comparing himself to [[Noah]] before the flood.<ref name=\"O'connor\"/> The track also includes a reference to West replacing ''Yandhi'' with ''Jesus Is King'' due to him having vowed to only put out Christian hip hop after going through a [[born again|new birth]] experience.<ref name=\"NewYork\"/><ref name=\"O'connor\"/><ref name=\"Wheeler2019\">{{cite web |last1=Wheeler |first1=Andr\u00e9 |title=Chick-fil-A and Yeezy Boosts: what we learned from Kanye West's Jesus Is King |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/oct/25/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-new-album |work=The Guardian |accessdate=October 30, 2019 |date=October 25, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191030064726/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/oct/25/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-new-album |archive-date=October 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> West references his problematic relationship with both Christianity and his father Ray West on \"Follow God\".<ref name=\"cos\"/> In \"[[Closed on Sunday]]\", Kanye West emphasizes the traditional Christian doctrine of [[Sabbatarianism|Sunday Sabbatarianism]], referencing the fast-food chain [[Chick-fil-A]], which he praises for being closed on the [[Lord's Day]] in order to allow people to [[church attendance|attend church]] and rest.<ref name=\"Carlin2019\">{{cite web |last1=Carlin |first1=Shannon |title=The Internet Has Feelings About Kanye West's Song About Chick-fil-A |url=https://www.refinery29.com/en-us/2019/10/8623113/kanye-west-closed-on-sunday-chickfila-lyrics |publisher=[[Refinery29]] |accessdate=October 29, 2019 |language=English |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191028173904/https://www.refinery29.com/en-us/2019/10/8623113/kanye-west-closed-on-sunday-chickfila-lyrics |archive-date=October 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Schmitz2019\"/><ref name=\"Bassett\"/><ref name=\"O'connor\"/><ref name=\"ew\"/> West links the observance of the [[Sabbath in Christianity|Christian Sabbath]] with the \"end of imprisonment, slavery, and debt peonage.\"<ref name=\"Schmitz2019\"/>\n\n\"On God\" features West \"delivering I've-seen-the-mountaintop style preaching,\" with West being \"prodding and unconvincing in a soundscape where he was a compelling idol.\" Throughout the song, West makes it clear that he must be richer than the clergy.<ref name=\"ew\"/> West references the [[Thirteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Thirteenth Amendment]] to the [[United States Constitution]] that abolished slavery on \"On God\" and \"Hands On\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/heres-everything-that-happened-at-kanyes-nyc-jesus-is-king-event/|title=Here's Everything That Happened at Kanye's NYC ''Jesus Is King'' Event|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|accessdate=October 1, 2019|author=Zhang, Cat|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191001170508/https://pitchfork.com/news/heres-everything-that-happened-at-kanyes-nyc-jesus-is-king-event/|archive-date=October 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> This followed on from West having previously called for the repeal of the amendment in September and October 2018, which he did because of the [[Thirteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution#Penal labor exemption|penal labor exemption]] that suggests that the enslavement of convicts is legal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5411662/kanye-west-13th-amendment-tweets-fact-check/|title=What Kanye West Got Right and Wrong About the 13th Amendment, According to Historians|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=October 2, 2018|accessdate=October 2, 2019|first=Olivia B.|last=Waxman|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190621220713/https://time.com/5411662/kanye-west-13th-amendment-tweets-fact-check/|archive-date=June 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Trump\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/remarks-president-trump-meeting-kanye-west-jim-brown/|title=Remarks by President Trump in Meeting with Kanye West and Jim Brown|publisher=[[White House]]|date=October 11, 2018|accessdate=October 1, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191001171634/https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/remarks-president-trump-meeting-kanye-west-jim-brown/|archive-date=October 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The imagery used in \"Water\" is a reference to the Christian [[sacrament]] of [[baptism]].<ref name=\"Becklo2019\">{{cite web |last1=Becklo |first1=Matthew |title=Jesus is King\u2014but is Kanye a believer? |url=https://aleteia.org/2019/10/25/jesus-is-king-but-is-kanye-a-believer/ |publisher=[[Aleteia]] |accessdate=October 29, 2019 |date=October 25, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191028230250/https://aleteia.org/2019/10/25/jesus-is-king-but-is-kanye-a-believer/ |archive-date=October 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> On \"[[Everything We Need]]\", West delivers \"Kanye-isms\" about [[Eve]] making [[apple juice]], while Ty Dolla Sign and Ant Clemon deliver [[rapture|rapturous]] vocals.<ref name=\"ew\"/> In ''Jesus Is King'', West teaches the doctrine of the [[Social Kingship of Christ]] through his advocation of \"defying worldly authorities\" and \"seek[ing] liberty from lower powers by submitting to a higher one.\"<ref name=\"Schmitz2019\">{{cite web |last1=Schmitz |first1=Matthew |title=Kanye was Christ-haunted long before 'Jesus Is King' |url=https://catholicherald.co.uk/commentandblogs/2019/10/28/kanye-was-christ-haunted-long-before-jesus-is-king/ |work=[[Catholic Herald]] |accessdate=October 29, 2019 |date=October 28, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191029235523/https://catholicherald.co.uk/commentandblogs/2019/10/28/kanye-was-christ-haunted-long-before-jesus-is-king/ |archive-date=October 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Release and promotion==\n<!--Formal announcements-->\n{{See also|Jesus Is King (film)}}\n[[File:Jesus is King - The Forum, LA (48951268196).jpg|thumb|250px|left|alt=[[The Forum (Inglewood, California)|The Forum]] in LA. Under ''Jesus is King'' listening party.|West previewed the album at [[The Forum (Inglewood, California)|The Forum]] in Los Angeles in October 2019.]]\nOriginally titled ''Yandhi'', the album was set for release on September 29, 2018, but was postponed to November 23, 2018. West later postponed the album again in the month that it had been first postponed to, though no new release date was set at the time.<ref name=\"NovDelay\"/> In January 2019, a representative for West denied a report claiming West was refusing to submit the album to gain leverage in a legal dispute with his record labels [[GOOD Music]] and Def Jam.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2019/01/kanye-west-sues-island-def-jam-and-refuses-to-turn-over-yandhi-album-report/|title=Kanye West Denies He Refuses to Submit 'Yandhi' Album|first=C. Vernon|last=Coleman II|work=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]|access-date=January 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190128030457/http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2019/01/kanye-west-sues-island-def-jam-and-refuses-to-turn-over-yandhi-album-report/|archive-date=January 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On August 29, 2019, Kardashian announced ''Jesus Is King'' with the release date of September 27, of that year, alongside a notebook featuring the track list via Instagram. A representative for West reported to ''[[E! News]]'' that ''Jesus Is King'' would be his \"latest album.\"<ref name=\"ENews\">{{Cite news|title=Kanye West Is Bringing His Sunday Services to Fans' Homes With New Album ''Jesus Is King''|date=August 30, 2019|accessdate=September 9, 2019|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/1022643/kanye-west-is-bringing-his-sunday-services-to-fans-homes-with-new-album-jesus-is-king|author=Contreras, Cydney|website=[[E! News]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190831053503/https://www.eonline.com/news/1022643/kanye-west-is-bringing-his-sunday-services-to-fans-homes-with-new-album-jesus-is-king|archive-date=August 31, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> During a Sunday Service performance on September 16, 2019, West reconfirmed the release date that Kardashian had tweeted out.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/kanye-west-announces-new-album-jesus-king-next-month-check-tracklist-2543368|title=Kanye West confirms release date of new album 'Jesus Is King'|date=September 17, 2019|accessdate=September 21, 2019|work=NME|first=Will|last=Richards|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190921203156/https://www.nme.com/news/music/kanye-west-announces-new-album-jesus-king-next-month-check-tracklist-2543368|archive-date=September 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn September 27, 2019, following a Sunday Service performance in [[Detroit]], West previewed the album and the accompanying film also entitled ''Jesus Is King'' at the [[Fox Theatre (Detroit)|Fox Theatre]]. Kardashian then announced that the former had been pushed back two days to be released on September 29, 2019, stating that mixing had to be finalized and that there'd be two more listening sessions in Chicago and New York.<ref name=\"Mixing\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8531647/inside-kanye-west-jesus-is-king-album-detroit-sunday-release|title=Kanye West Plays 'Jesus Is King' Album for Eager Detroit Crowd Ahead of Sunday Release: Inside the Event|first=Gary|last=Graff|date=September 27, 2019|accessdate=September 28, 2019|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190928041736/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8531647/inside-kanye-west-jesus-is-king-album-detroit-sunday-release|archive-date=September 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/kanye-west-is-releasing-new-album-jesus-is-king-on-sunday-kim-says/|title=Kanye West Is Releasing New Album ''Jesus Is King'' on Sunday, Kim Says|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|first=Madison|last=Bloom|date=September 27, 2019|accessdate=September 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190928090222/https://pitchfork.com/news/kanye-west-is-releasing-new-album-jesus-is-king-on-sunday-kim-says/|archive-date=September 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The album also missed that date with no explanation provided by either West or Kardashian.<ref name=\"NewYork\"/> On October 12, 2019, West announced a tentative release date of October 25, 2019 at a [[Washington, D.C.]] listening party.<ref name=\"Oct19\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/10/kanye-west-reportedly-announces-new-release-date-jesus-is-king|title=Kanye West Reportedly Announces New Release Date for 'Jesus Is King' Album|first=Joshua|last=Espinoza|date=October 12, 2019|accessdate=October 13, 2019|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191013161735/https://www.complex.com/music/2019/10/kanye-west-reportedly-announces-new-release-date-jesus-is-king|archive-date=October 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> West ultimately confirmed via Twitter on October 21 that this was the official release date and pre-ordering for ''Jesus Is King'' began the following day.<ref name=\"pitchfork\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/kanye-west-says-new-album-jesus-is-king-is-out-this-week/|title=Kanye West Says New Album Jesus Is King Is Out This Week|last1=Monroe|first1=Jazz|last2=Minsker|first2=Evan|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=October 21, 2019|accessdate=October 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191021060603/https://pitchfork.com/news/kanye-west-says-new-album-jesus-is-king-is-out-this-week/|archive-date=October 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"complex\">{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/10/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-album-release-date|title=Kanye West Announces New Album 'Jesus Is King' Will Be Released This Week|last=Ortiz|first=Edwin|website=Complex|date=October 21, 2019|accessdate=October 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191021060600/https://www.complex.com/music/2019/10/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-album-release-date|archive-date=October 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hypebeast.com/2019/10/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-new-release-date-album-pre-order|title=Kanye West Launches 'Jesus Is King' Pre-Orders (Update)|work=Hypebeast|access-date=October 22, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191022181150/https://hypebeast.com/2019/10/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-new-release-date-album-pre-order|archive-date=October 22, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The album and its accompanying film were previewed again at [[The Forum (Inglewood, California)|The Forum]] in Los Angeles on October 23, 2019, for 17,000 attendees, two days before the release of them.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ju|first=Shirley|url=https://variety.com/2019/music/news/kanye-west-previews-jesus-is-king-in-los-angeles-a-view-from-the-forum-floor-1203381698/|title=Kanye West Previews 'Jesus Is King' in Los Angeles: A View From the Forum Floor|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=October 24, 2019|access-date=November 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191028173056/https://variety.com/2019/music/news/kanye-west-previews-jesus-is-king-in-los-angeles-a-view-from-the-forum-floor-1203381698/|archive-date=October 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<!--JIK live performances -->\n[[File:James Turrell - Rendering for Aten Reign - Photo 01.jpg|thumb|right|alt=Rendering of the [[Roden Crater]]|Rendering of the [[Roden Crater]], the shooting location of the ''Jesus Is King'' film.]]\nOn October 25, 2019, ''Jesus Is King'' was released for [[Music download|digital download]] and [[Streaming media|streaming]] by GOOD Music, distributed by Def Jam Recordings.<ref name=\"Released\"/> The album's release was simultaneous with that of an [[Experimental film|experimental]] [[Concert film|concert]] short film [[Jesus Is King (film)|of the same name]], directed by [[Nick Knight (photographer)|Nick Knight]]. The film was shot over the summer of 2019 at the [[Roden Crater]] in [[Painted Desert (Arizona)|Painted Desert, Arizona]], and features the Sunday Service Choir. It was released in [[IMAX]] theaters, with numerous tracks from the album being included as part of the soundtrack.<ref name=\"Film\"/><ref>{{Cite web|last=Curto|first=Justin|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/10/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-movie-everything-to-know.html|title=Everything in Kanye West's 'Jesus Is King' Movie|publisher=Vulture|date=October 25, 2019|access-date=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191025174347/https://www.vulture.com/2019/10/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-movie-everything-to-know.html|archive-date=October 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Prior to the latter's release, West had performed the song \"Water\" live with the Sunday Service Choir in April 2019.<ref name=\"Water\"/> When premiering the song, West announced it as a new track.<ref name=\"Water\"/> \"Water\" was ultimately released as the seventh track on ''Jesus Is King'' in October 2019.<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/> Various churches across the state of Texas have revealed that they won't play the album, and it has also been predicted by numerous people involved with Christianity to not be played on [[Christian radio]] stations across the state.<ref>{{cite news|last=Skinner|first=Paige|url=https://www.dallasobserver.com/music/churches-say-they-will-not-be-playing-kanye-wests-new-gospel-album-11800214|title=Churches Say They Will Not be Playing Kanye West's New Gospel Album|website=[[Dallas Observer]]|date=November 16, 2019|access-date=November 17, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191117124842/https://www.dallasobserver.com/music/churches-say-they-will-not-be-playing-kanye-wests-new-gospel-album-11800214|archive-date=November 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Jesus Is King'' was released as a [[Compact disc|CD]] in the United States on March 27, 2020 through West's record labels.<ref name=\"Cd\"/>\n\nThe cover art for ''Jesus Is King'' is a blue [[Phonograph record|vinyl]], with the album's title and West's name being written at the top and the bottom, respectively. The art contains text on the left reading \"New Songs AR 1331 A,\" while 33RPMLP is written on the right. After confusion of what \"AR 1331 A\" meant, [[Third Man Records]] co-founder [[Ben Blackwell]] explained that the text is the [[Archer Records]] (AR) pressing plant code assigned to the 1970 A-Side gospel single by Rubye Shelton that consists of \"I Want The World To Know Jesus\" and \"God's Going To Destroy This Nation\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/kanye-wests-jesus-is-king-album-art-mystery-has-been-solved-news.94698.html|title=Kanye West's \"Jesus Is King\" Album Art Mystery Has Been Solved|date=November 1, 2019|accessdate=December 9, 2019|website=HotNewHipHop|first=Aron|last=A.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191208063959/https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/kanye-wests-jesus-is-king-album-art-mystery-has-been-solved-news.94698.html|archive-date=December 8, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> At the time of ''Jesus Is King'' being released, West simultaneously launched \"a clothing line depicting Christ blessing the people.\"<ref name=\"CP2019\">{{cite web |title=Kanye West Debuts \"Jesus is King\" Album & Clothing: \"He's Making it Cool to Praise God\" |url=https://churchpop.com/2019/09/28/kanye-west-debuts-jesus-is-king-album-clothing-hes-making-it-cool-to-praise-god/ |publisher=ChurchPOP |language=English |date=September 28, 2019 |accessdate=October 30, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191030005127/https://churchpop.com/2019/09/28/kanye-west-debuts-jesus-is-king-album-clothing-hes-making-it-cool-to-praise-god/ |archive-date=October 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> After its launch, the ''Jesus Is King'' clothing line had sold out.<ref name=\"CP2019\"/> The apparel in the ''Jesus is King'' clothing line features the album name and \"includes a T-shirt, long-sleeved shirt, crewneck and hooded sweatshirts, sweatpants and baseball caps.\"<ref name=\"Kirkpatrick2019\">{{cite web |last1=Kirkpatrick |first1=Emily |title=Kanye West releases 'Jesus Is King' merch |url=https://pagesix.com/2019/10/25/kanye-west-releases-jesus-is-king-merch/ |publisher=[[Page Six]] |accessdate=October 30, 2019 |language=English |date=October 25, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191028233740/https://pagesix.com/2019/10/25/kanye-west-releases-jesus-is-king-merch/ |archive-date=October 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn October 27, 2019, West and his choir performed the first Sunday Service since the album's release at The Forum, with songs from it being performed.<ref name=\"oct28\">{{cite news|last=France|first=Lisa Respers|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/10/28/entertainment/kanye-west-sunday-service-trnd/index.html|title=Kanye West holds first Sunday Service since album release|publisher=CNN|date=October 28, 2019|access-date=November 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191115151616/https://edition.cnn.com/2019/10/28/entertainment/kanye-west-sunday-service-trnd/index.html|archive-date=November 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Songs from ''The Life of Pablo'' were performed as well, which Kardashian referenced on Twitter, while she also tweeted out in excitement over the event.<ref name=\"oct28\"/> West performed songs from ''Jesus Is King'' with his choir in front of inmates at two jails in Houston, Texas, on November 15.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lewis|first=Sophie|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/jesus-is-king-kanye-west-performs-new-album-for-hundreds-of-inmates-at-houston-prisons-before-lakewood-church-event/|title=Jesus Is King: Kanye West performs new album for hundreds of inmates at Houston prisons|publisher=[[CBS News]]|date=November 16, 2019|access-date=November 17, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191117021634/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/jesus-is-king-kanye-west-performs-new-album-for-hundreds-of-inmates-at-houston-prisons-before-lakewood-church-event/|archive-date=November 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On November 16, 2019, it was announced that West would be performing at [[Joel Osteen]]'s [[Lakewood Church]] the next day to promote the album.<ref name=\"cnn\">{{cite news|last=III|first=Fernando Alfonso|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/11/16/us/kanye-west-lakewood-church-ticket-scalping-trnd/index.html|title=Kanye West is performing at Joel Osteen's megachurch on Sunday. People are scalping tickets for $250|publisher=CNN|date=November 16, 2019|access-date=November 17, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191117003626/https://edition.cnn.com/2019/11/16/us/kanye-west-lakewood-church-ticket-scalping-trnd/index.html|archive-date=November 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Simultaneously, tickets were made available for free through Ticketmaster, and were gone within seven minutes.<ref name=\"cnn\"/> Scalpers immediately began selling them on Twitter and Craig's List at up to $250 each.<ref name=\"cnn\"/> The event was called the \"Sunday Service Experience\", with it including West and the Sunday Service Choir performing, though the event was open to fans of all faiths despite being centered around Christianity.<ref>{{cite news|last=Miles|first=Frank|url=https://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/kanye-west-joel-osteen-lakewood-church-sunday-service-experience|title=Kanye West performs free 'Sunday Service Experience' concert at Joel Osteen's Lakewood Church|publisher=[[Fox News]]|date=November 18, 2019|access-date=November 19, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191118045804/https://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/kanye-west-joel-osteen-lakewood-church-sunday-service-experience|archive-date=November 18, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Tracks from ''Jesus Is King'' were performed alongside material that West released earlier in his career, including \"[[Jesus Walks]]\" (2004).<ref name=\"cnn\"/> As well as this, gospel remixes were performed of [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] ballads, notably [[SMV (band)|SMV]]'s \"[[Weak (SWV song)|Weak]]\" (1993) and [[Destiny Child]]'s \"[[Say My Name]]\" (1999).<ref name=\"cnn\"/>\n\n===Promotion for ''Yandhi'' and leaks===\nWest performed the single \"I Love It\" with Lil Pump and \"We Got Love\", a duet with Taylor featuring a pre-recorded voice memo by [[Lauryn Hill]], on the season 44 premiere of ''SNL'' that coincided with the original release date for ''Yandhi''. West closed the show by performing \"[[Ghost Town (Kanye West song)|Ghost Town]]\" from ''Ye'' with Kid Cudi and [[070 Shake]] and giving a speech in support of US president [[Donald Trump]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/kanye-and-lil-pump-dressed-as-water-bottles-perform-i-love-it-on-snl/|title=Kanye Storms \"SNL\" With 3 Wild Performances, Political Speech: Watch|first=Michelle|last=Kim|date=September 30, 2018|accessdate=October 1, 2019|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191026120450/https://pitchfork.com/news/kanye-and-lil-pump-dressed-as-water-bottles-perform-i-love-it-on-snl/|archive-date=October 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> After the SNL performance, full-size costumes from the \"I Love It\" music video were put up for sale online.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/kanye-west-i-love-it-costume-buy-now/|title=YEEZY SUPPLY Is Selling the Costumes from Kanye's \"I Love It\" Music Video|date=30 September 2019|accessdate=14 December 2019|work=Highsnobiety|author=Gorsler, Fabian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214155656/https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/kanye-west-i-love-it-costume-buy-now/|archive-date=December 14, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> West recorded a music video for \"We Got Love\" with Taylor on October 1, 2018, in the [[TMZ]] parking lot,<ref name=\"TMZ\"/> though the music video was never released. West then revealed to TMZ that he had a song about [[body shaming]] featuring Minaj and Ty Dolla Sign on ''Yandhi''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hypebeast.com/2018/10/kanye-west-yandhi-features-nicki-minaj-ty-dolla-sign|title=Kanye West & Nicki Minaj Will Tackle Body Shaming on 'Yandhi'|work=Hypebeat|date=October 24, 2019|accessdate=December 20, 2019|author=Montes, Patrick|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191221000628/https://hypebeast.com/2018/10/kanye-west-yandhi-features-nicki-minaj-ty-dolla-sign|archive-date=December 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The recording of Minaj's verse on the song, entitled \"New Body\", was prominently showcased in an April 2019 episode of American television series ''[[Keeping Up with the Kardashians]]''.<ref name=\"KUWTKs16e2\"/> Following the airing of the episode, Kardashian discussed the writing of the song on [[Twitter]].<ref name=\"Verse\"/> \"I Love It\", \"We Got Love\", and \"New Body\" were all initially intended for ''Yandhi''.<ref name=\"KUWTKs16e2\"/> \"We Got Love\" was later released as a single by Taylor on December 6, 2019.<ref name=\"WeGotLove\"/>\n\nIn July 2019, tracks dated from a late-December 2018 session of ''Yandhi'' began [[Internet|leaking online]], including \"New Body\" featuring Nicki Minaj and Ty Dolla Sign, \"The Storm\" featuring XXXTentacion, Ty Dolla Sign, and Clemons, a solo track entitled \"Spread Your Wings\", and demos of \"Alien / SpaceX\" and \"Law of Attraction\", with both demos featuring Clemons.<ref name=\"LeakNewBody01\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/whats-with-all-the-leaks-kanye-west-and-nicki-minaj-21-savage-young-thug-and-more-news.85403.html|title=What's With All The Leaks? Kanye West & Nicki Minaj, 21 Savage, Young Thug & More|date=July 11, 2019|website=HotNewHipHop|first=Alex|last=Zidel|accessdate=July 11, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190711204104/https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/whats-with-all-the-leaks-kanye-west-and-nicki-minaj-21-savage-young-thug-and-more-news.85403.html|archive-date=July 11, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genius.com/a/multiple-songs-from-kanye-west-s-yandhi-surface-online|title=Multiple Songs From Kanye West's 'Yandhi' Surface Online|date=July 15, 2019|accessdate=September 20, 2019|website=[[Genius (website)|Genius]]|first=Chris|last=Mench|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190717155123/https://genius.com/a/multiple-songs-from-kanye-west-s-yandhi-surface-online|archive-date=July 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The leaks were precipitated by \"group buys\", which are online money-pooling efforts organized by fans in order to purchase the tracks from a well-known leaker. Producers who worked on \"Law of Attraction\" denounced the leak of their track as an \"invasion of privacy,\"<ref name=\"LeakReaction\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/kanye-leaked-song-new-track-listen-yandhi-1450010|title=Why Kanye's people don't want you to listen to his new song...yet|date=July 18, 2019|accessdate=September 19, 2019|last=Wynne|first=Kelly|work=[[Newsweek]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902043524/https://www.newsweek.com/kanye-leaked-song-new-track-listen-yandhi-1450010|archive-date=September 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Attraction\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/kanye-west-law-of-attraction-leak/|title=Leaked Kanye West Track \"Law of Attraction\" Surfaces Online|first=Sarah|last=Osei|date=July 18, 2019|accessdate=July 18, 2019|work=[[Highsnobiety]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190718124308/https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/kanye-west-law-of-attraction-leak/|archive-date=July 18, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> while the track was ultimately scrapped and re-recorded as \"Use This Gospel\" for release on ''Jesus Is King''.<ref name=\"ev\">{{cite web |last1=Mehta |first1=Adi |url=http://entertainmentvoice.com/2019/10/25/yeezus-turns-to-jesus-kanye-west-preaches-on-gospel-influenced-jesus-is-king-album/ |title=Yeezus Turns to Jesus: Kanye West Preaches the Gospel on 'Jesus Is King' Album |website=Entertainment Voice |date=October 2019 |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402150535/http://entertainmentvoice.com/2019/10/25/yeezus-turns-to-jesus-kanye-west-preaches-on-gospel-influenced-jesus-is-king-album/ |archive-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> Of the ''Yandhi'' leaks, Pusha T wrote on Twitter that \"it ruins all that we have in store for [you] guys.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2019/08/27/pusha-t-blasts-yandhi-leak-it-ruins-all-that-we-have-in-store-for-u-guys|title=Pusha T blasts ''Yandhi'' leak: \"It ruins all that we have in store for u guys\"|work=The Fader|first=Jordan|last=Darville|date=August 27, 2019|accessdate=September 5, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190903195341/https://www.thefader.com/2019/08/27/pusha-t-blasts-yandhi-leak-it-ruins-all-that-we-have-in-store-for-u-guys|archive-date=September 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Paul Thompson, writing for ''The Fader'', noted that the leaks didn't receive mainstream attention and were a \"minor story\" compared to West songs that had leaked previously. Thompson cited factors such as the lukewarm reception of ''Ye'' and that songs don't typically enter \"popular canon\" nowadays unless they're released on streaming services.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2019/08/23/yandhi-and-the-legacy-of-kanye-west-leaks|title=''Yandhi'' and the Legacy of Kanye West leaks|work=The Fader|first=Paul|last=Thompson|date=August 23, 2019|accessdate=August 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190824235702/https://www.thefader.com/2019/08/23/yandhi-and-the-legacy-of-kanye-west-leaks|archive-date=August 24, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> \"Everything We Need\" was recorded as a new version of the track \"The Storm\", with the former being released on ''Jesus Is King''.<ref name=\"Nguyen\"/> In December 2019, the track \"Bye Bye Baby\" leaked online, featuring opening vocals by American rapper [[Mykki Blanco]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/kanye-west-bye-bye-baby-yandhi-leak/|title=Listen to Leaked Kanye West Track \"Bye Bye Baby\" Before It's Taken Down|author=Sarah Osei|date=December 19, 2019|accessdate=January 17, 2019|website=Highsnobiety}}</ref>\n\n===Singles===\nA [[Music video#Lyric videos|lyric video]] for \"Follow God\" premiered on October 26, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|last=Vetrici|first=Marcus|url=https://www.sohh.com/watch-kanye-wests-follow-god-lyric-video-has-arrived/|title=Watch: Kanye West's Follow God Lyric Video Has Arrived|website=[[SOHH]]|date=October 26, 2019|access-date=October 31, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191031002754/https://www.sohh.com/watch-kanye-wests-follow-god-lyric-video-has-arrived/|archive-date=October 31, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On November 5, the song was selected by West for release as ''Jesus Is King''{{'}}s lead single in the US.<ref name=\"rhythmic\">{{Cite news |url=https://hiphop-n-more.com/2019/11/kanye-west-picks-follow-god-as-lead-single-from-jesus-is-king/ |title=Kanye West Picks 'Follow God' As Lead Single From 'Jesus is King' |author=Navjosh |date=November 5, 2019 |website=HipHop-N-More |access-date=November 7, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191107055814/https://hiphop-n-more.com/2019/11/kanye-west-picks-follow-god-as-lead-single-from-jesus-is-king/ |archive-date=November 7, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The song was serviced to [[Contemporary hit radio|mainstream radio]] stations across the United Kingdom on November 8, 2019, through West's record labels as the first single in the UK.<ref name=\"mainstream\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio1/playlist |title=Radio 1 \u2013 Playlist |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=November 8, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191108203823/https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/3tqPdBWF9yMbTrfjWvfKV8t/radio-1-playlist |archivedate=November 8, 2019 |accessdate=November 9, 2019}}</ref> That same day, an accompanying music video was released. Within the video, West and his father walk together in snow, while the two of them also drive ATV's in the visual.<ref>{{cite news|last=Heller|first=Corinne|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/1091203/kanye-west-bonds-with-his-dad-in-follow-god-music-video|title=Kanye West Bonds With His Dad in \"Follow God\" Music Video|website=E! News|date=November 8, 2019|access-date=December 14, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191110040126/https://www.eonline.com/uk/news/1091203/kanye-west-bonds-with-his-dad-in-follow-god-music-video|archive-date=November 10, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On November 12 of the same year, \"Follow God\" was sent to US [[Airplay|radio]] stations by West's record labels as the lead single from the album.<ref name=\"rhythmic\"/> The song reached number seven on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] prior to release as a single, becoming West's 18th top ten entry on the chart.<ref name=\"hundred\"/> Similarly, it peaked at number six on the [[UK Singles Chart]], standing as West's 23rd top ten single on the chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/hughmcintyre/2019/11/02/selena-gomez-kanye-west-and-lizzo-score-new-top-10-singles-in-the-uk/|title=Selena Gomez, Kanye West And Lizzo Score New Top 10 Singles In The U.K.|work=Forbes|last=McIntyre|first=Hugh|date=November 2, 2019|accessdate=November 17, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191105115223/https://www.forbes.com/sites/hughmcintyre/2019/11/02/selena-gomez-kanye-west-and-lizzo-score-new-top-10-singles-in-the-uk/|archive-date=November 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On December 9, 2019, \"Follow God\" was certified [[RIAA certification|gold]] in the US by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) for sales of 500,000 certified units.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&ar=Kanye+West&ti=Follow+God#search_section|title=Gold & Platinum \u2212 Kanye West \u2212 Follow God|publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]]|accessdate=December 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n\"Closed on Sunday\" was released as the second single from ''Jesus Is King'' on November 28, 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/kanye-west-closed-on-sunday-music-video-919422/|title=Kanye West Brings Family and a Choir to 'Closed on Sunday' Video|website=Rolling Stone|first1=Jon|last1=Blistein|first2=Jon|last2=Blistein|date=November 28, 2019|accessdate=March 29, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203160832/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/kanye-west-closed-on-sunday-music-video-919422/|archive-date=February 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Elle\">{{Cite web|last1=Blair|first1=Olivia|url=https://www.elle.com/uk/life-and-culture/culture/a30053478/kanye-west-video-closed-on-sunday-kim-kardashian-kids/|title=Kanye West Closed On Sunday Video Stars Kim Kardashian, North West And Kids|website=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle UK]]|date=November 29, 2019|accessdate=March 29, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191227204010/https://www.elle.com/uk/life-and-culture/culture/a30053478/kanye-west-video-closed-on-sunday-kim-kardashian-kids/|archive-date=December 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> That same day, an accompanying music video for the track was released, coinciding with the date of [[Thanksgiving]] in the US for that year. The video features West cuddling with Kardashian and the couple's children North, Saint, Chicago, and Psalm West, and the family walk hand-in-hand within the visual.<ref name=\"Elle\"/> The track debuted at number 17 and 19 on the US ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and UK Singles Chart, respectively, before being released as a single.<ref name=\"hundred\"/><ref name=\"McIntyre\"/>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| ADM = 4.9/10<ref name=\"AnyDecentMusic\">{{cite web|title=Jesus Is King by Kanye West Reviews|url=http://anydecentmusic.com/review/10140/Kanye-West-Jesus-Is-King.aspx|publisher=[[AnyDecentMusic?]]|accessdate=November 1, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191028191349/http://anydecentmusic.com/review/10140/Kanye-West-Jesus-Is-King.aspx|archive-date=October 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| MC = 53/100<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/jesus-is-king/kanye-west|title=Jesus Is King by Kanye West Reviews and Tracks|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=January 10, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191101194450/https://www.metacritic.com/music/jesus-is-king/kanye-west|archive-date=November 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/jesus-is-king-mw0003318875 |title=Jesus Is King \u2013 Kanye West |last=Yeung |first=Neil Z. |date=October 31, 2019 |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |access-date=October 31, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191026202926/https://www.allmusic.com/album/jesus-is-king-mw0003318875 |archive-date=October 26, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''\n| rev2score = {{Rating|2|4}}<ref name=\"Kot\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/music/greg-kot/sc-ent-kanye-west-jesus-is-king-review-1025-20191025-3n6wn3ej75aszd3fdqilp3wxpm-story.html |title=Kanye West review: 'Jesus Is King' puts gospel message ahead of musicality |last=Kot |first=Greg |authorlink=Greg Kot |date=October 25, 2019 |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |access-date=October 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191028025521/https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/music/greg-kot/sc-ent-kanye-west-jesus-is-king-review-1025-20191025-3n6wn3ej75aszd3fdqilp3wxpm-story.html |archive-date=October 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''\n| rev3score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Tele\">{{cite news|last=McCormick|first=Neil|author-link=Neil McCormick|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/what-to-listen-to/kanye-west-jesus-king-album-review-unlikely-evangelical-musical/|title=Kanye West: Jesus Is King, album review: the most unlikely evangelical musical turnaround since Bob Dylan|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=October 26, 2019|accessdate=October 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191026193022/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/what-to-listen-to/kanye-west-jesus-king-album-review-unlikely-evangelical-musical/|archive-date=October 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev4score = C+<ref name=\"ew\">{{Cite web |url=https://ew.com/music-reviews/2019/10/28/kanye-west-unreliable-pastor-jesus-is-king/ |title=Kanye West is an unreliable pastor on Jesus Is King |last=Josephs |first=Brian |date=October 28, 2019 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |access-date=November 1, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191101075216/https://ew.com/music-reviews/2019/10/28/kanye-west-unreliable-pastor-jesus-is-king/ |archive-date=November 1, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Exclaim!]]''\n| rev5score = 6/10<ref>{{cite web|last=Chini|first=Joey|url=https://exclaim.ca/music/article/kanye_west-jesus_is_king|title=Kanye West Jesus Is King|work=[[Exclaim!]]|date=October 27, 2019|accessdate=October 29, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191028191404/http://exclaim.ca/music/article/kanye_west-jesus_is_king|archive-date=October 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev6score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=\"Nguyen\">{{cite web|last=Nguyen|first=Dean Van|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/oct/26/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-review|title=Kanye West: Jesus Is King review \u2013 rap genius can't see the light|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=October 26, 2019|accessdate=October 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191026155013/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/oct/26/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-review|archive-date=October 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[The Independent]]''\n| rev7score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=\"O'connor\">{{cite web|last=O'Connor|first=Roisin|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-review-album-stream-tracklist-features-lyrics-sunday-service-a9171816.html|title=Kanye West review, 'Jesus is King': Rapper continues to divide on this confusing album|work=[[The Independent]]|date=October 25, 2019|accessdate=October 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191025210548/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-review-album-stream-tracklist-features-lyrics-sunday-service-a9171816.html|archive-date=October 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev8score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Bassett\">{{cite web|last=Bassett|first=Jordan|url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/album/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-review|title=Kanye West \u2013 'Jesus Is King' review: an iconoclast sounds peaceful and fulfilled on this jubilant gospel collection|website=NME|date=October 25, 2019|accessdate=October 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191025210547/https://www.nme.com/reviews/album/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-review|archive-date=October 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev9score = 7.2/10<ref name=\"Kameir\">{{cite web|last=Kameir|first=Rawiya|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/kanye-west-jesus-is-king/|title=Kanye West: Jesus Is King|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=October 28, 2019|accessdate=October 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191029051120/https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/kanye-west-jesus-is-king/|archive-date=October 29, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev10score = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref name=\"Klinkenberg\">{{cite web|last=Klinkenberg|first=Brendan|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/kanye-wests-jesus-is-king-904921/|title=Review: Kanye West, 'Jesus Is King'|work=Rolling Stone|date=October 28, 2019|accessdate=October 29, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191028235236/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/kanye-wests-jesus-is-king-904921/|archive-date=October 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Jesus Is King'' was met with mixed reviews from music critics. At [[Metacritic]], the album received an [[Weighted arithmetic mean|average]] score of 53, based on 25 reviews.<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/> Aggregator [[AnyDecentMusic?]] gave ''Jesus Is King'' 4.9 out of 10, based on their assessment of the critical consensus.<ref name=\"AnyDecentMusic\"/>\n\nJordan Bassett from ''[[NME]]'' wrote of the album: \"Where last year's truncated, seven-track {{'}}''ye''{{'}} largely felt sterile and unfinished, a collection of messy, half-realised conceits, here is an album with absolute clarity and confidence.\"<ref name=\"Bassett\" /> Bassett continued, calling it \"concise by\" the standards of Kanye West but not one of his \"masterworks\" like ''My Beautiful Dark Twisted Fantasy'' and ''The Life of Pablo'', though asserted that \"there's density and focus throughout.\"<ref name=\"Bassett\" /> McCormick expressed similar feelings, stating that \"with gospel choirs, church organs and soulful ululations condensed into a typically bravura tableaux of obscure samples, warped synths and spooky slabs of vocoder harmonies, ''Jesus Is King'' sounds as scintillating as anything\" from West's discography.<ref name=\"Tele\"/> Writing for ''[[The New York Times]]'', [[Jon Caramanica]] said of the album: \"A more engaged and vivid album than {{'}}''Ye''{{'}} from last year, though nowhere as robust as {{'}}''The Life of Pablo''{{'}} from 2016, it is bare-bones and curiously effective,\" praising the emotion but being less enthusiastic towards the album's structure.<ref name=\"Caramanica\">{{cite web|last=Caramanica|first=Jon|author-link=Jon Caramanica|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/27/arts/music/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-review.html|title=Kanye West, Heretic by Nature, Finds God|work=The New York Times|date=October 28, 2019|accessdate=October 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191028014249/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/27/arts/music/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-review.html|archive-date=October 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Rawiya Kameir from ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' called it \"a markedly more cohesive and enjoyable album than I believed him capable of creating at this juncture\" but criticized ''Jesus Is King'' for being \"largely focused on the ways in which religion has served Kanye himself.\"<ref name=\"Kameir\" /> Sam C. Mac of ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' was positive towards the production, though panned West's lack of capability to \"translate his spiritual awakening to his music as confidently as he has nearly every other experience in his life on previous albums,\" despite noting that it \"isn't the work of a has-been\" and \"there are flashes of genius throughout.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Mac|first=Sam C.|title=Review: Kanye West's Jesus Is King Is a Compelling But Veiled Act of Self-Worship|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review-kanye-west-jesus-is-king-is-a-compelling-but-veiled-act-of-self-worship/|work=[[Slant Magazine]]|date=October 30, 2019|accessdate=October 30, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191030195321/https://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review-kanye-west-jesus-is-king-is-a-compelling-but-veiled-act-of-self-worship/|archive-date=October 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn a mixed review, ''Rolling Stone''{{'}}s Brendan Klinkenberg looked at the album as where West is \"no longer poking at contradictions, but reveling in a newfound zeal,\" though concluded by writing that \"it will likely be placed alongside ''ye''\" in West's discography \"as a distinctly lightweight entry\" despite being \"filled with moments of undeniable brilliance.\"<ref name=\"Klinkenberg\"/> [[Greg Kot]] of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' stated that West's \"element of surprise, conflict and musical tension is largely missing\" from ''Jesus Is King'' and labeled it as \"a pedestrian effort from an artist who was anything but for the first decade of his career,\" despite pointing to certain gospel moments as \"musical sparks\" due to \"West allowing message to trump musicality.\"<ref name=\"Kot\"/> Ross Horton was somewhat negative in ''[[The Line of Best Fit]]'', expressing the viewpoint that the album \"isn't even as hilariously shit or infuriatingly offensive as ''Ye'',\" and continuing by stating that \"it's one great tune and a bunch of other ideas, and it isn't entertaining in the slightest.\"<ref name=\"Horton\">{{cite web|last=Horton|first=Ross|url=https://www.thelineofbestfit.com/reviews/albums/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-album-review|title=Kanye West \u2013 Jesus Is King {{!}} Album Review|website=[[The Line of Best Fit]]|date=October 26, 2019|accessdate=October 30, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191027001238/https://www.thelineofbestfit.com/reviews/albums/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-album-review|archive-date=October 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> For ''[[The Guardian]]'', Dean Van Nguyen called the album \"too slight a record, too lacking in substance, to offer any sense of purification or real insights into West's mind\" and branded it as \"perfunctory religious discussion that tell us little of God's place in the life of this one believer and almost nothing\" about the former's place in the modern world.<ref name=\"Nguyen\"/> In another negative review, Wren Graves from ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'' gave the album an \"F\" rating, viewing it as \"27 minutes of cliches, half-finished thoughts, and vaguely religious gesturing,\" while claiming that the album \"feels surprisingly long\" and writing: \"Ideas develop and fizzle, but nothing sticks.\"<ref name=\"cos\">{{Cite web |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2019/10/album-review-kanye-west-jesus-is-king/ |title=Kanye West Even Bores God with the Passionless Jesus Is King |last=Graves |first=Wren |date=October 28, 2019 |work=Consequence of Sound |access-date=October 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191028191359/https://consequenceofsound.net/2019/10/album-review-kanye-west-jesus-is-king/ |archive-date=October 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n''Jesus Is King'' appeared on year-end best album lists for 2019 by multiple publications. On ''Rolling Stone''{{'}}s list of the best hip hop albums of the year, the album was ranked at number 16.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Klinkenberg |first1=Brendan |last2=Holmes |first2=Charles |last3=Leight |first3=Elias |title=20 Best Hip-Hop Albums of 2019 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/20-best-hip-hop-albums-of-2019-931888/ |website=Rolling Stone |date=December 30, 2019 |accessdate=February 21, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221065943/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/20-best-hip-hop-albums-of-2019-931888/ |archive-date=February 21, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> It was listed at the same position on the list of 2019's best foreign albums by ''[[Afisha|Afisha Daily]]'', from Russia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://daily.afisha.ru/music/13948-luchshie-zarubezhnye-albomy-2019-goda/|trans-title=The Best Foreign Albums of 2019|title=\u041b\u0443\u0447\u0448\u0438\u0435 \u0437\u0430\u0440\u0443\u0431\u0435\u0436\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0430\u043b\u044c\u0431\u043e\u043c\u044b 2019 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430|website=[[Afisha|Afisha Daily]]|language=Russian|date=December 26, 2019|accessdate=March 29, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205231846/https://daily.afisha.ru/music/13948-luchshie-zarubezhnye-albomy-2019-goda/|archive-date=February 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Complex'' named ''Jesus Is King'' as the 50th best album of the year, with Skelton praising the production but criticizing the songwriting, despite concluding that \"it's certainly worth a listen\" even with some faults.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/best-albums-2019/|title=Best Albums of 2019: Top Music Albums of the Year|work=Complex|date=December 3, 2019|accessdate=March 29, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200123065546/https://www.complex.com/music/best-albums-2019/|archive-date=January 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Caramanica ranked the album as the ninth best of 2019, complementing it for showing West channeling his older self.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pareles |first1=Jon |last2=Caramanica |first2=Jon |author-link=Jon Pareles |title=Best Albums of 2019 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/05/arts/music/best-albums.html |website=The New York Times |date=December 5, 2019 |accessdate=February 7, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101021644/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/05/arts/music/best-albums.html |archivedate=January 1, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> ''Jesus Is King'' was listed by ''[[The Mercury News]]'' as the 44th best album of the 2010s, with Jim Harrington writing of it: \"Arguably the boldest, bravest album of the decade.\"<ref>{{cite web |author1=Harrington, Jim |title=50 Best albums of the Decade: Lorde, Lana, Kanye, Kendrick and more |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2019/12/20/50-best-albums-of-the-decade-lorde-lana-kanye-kendrick-and-more/ |website=[[The Mercury News]] |accessdate=February 7, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114030239/https://www.mercurynews.com/2019/12/20/50-best-albums-of-the-decade-lorde-lana-kanye-kendrick-and-more/ |archivedate=January 14, 2020 |date=December 20, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\nOn the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], ''Jesus Is King'' opened at number one with 264,000 [[album-equivalent unit]]s, of which 109,000 were pure album sales, ranking as the second-largest sales week of 2019 for an R&B/hip-hop album.<ref name=\"BB200\"/> This gave West his ninth consecutive album to debut atop the chart, tying him with a record held by fellow rapper [[Eminem]].<ref name=\"BB200\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/8542364/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-billboard-200-debut-no-1|title=Kanye West's 'Jesus Is King' Arrives as His Record-Tying Ninth Consecutive No. 1 Debut on Billboard 200 Chart|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=November 3, 2019|accessdate=November 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191104110837/https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/8542364/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-billboard-200-debut-no-1|archive-date=November 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The chart-topping position stood as the sixth time that West did so with an album in the 2010s, tying him for second place with fellow rapper [[Future (rapper)|Future]] and Canadian singer [[Justin Bieber]] for most number one albums of the decade.<ref name=\"BB200\"/> The album simultaneously entered atop the US [[List of number-one Billboard Christian Albums|Top Christian Albums]] and [[Billboard charts#Top Gospel Albums|Top Gospel Albums]] charts.<ref name=\"BBCH\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/8542480/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-no-1-christian-gospel-album-charts|title=Kanye West's 'Jesus Is King' Is No 1 On Top Christian & Gospel Albums Charts|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Asker|first=Jim|date=November 4, 2019|accessdate=November 5, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191105010138/https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/8542480/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-no-1-christian-gospel-album-charts|archive-date=November 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> By doing so, ''Jesus Is King'' gave West his first appearance on the respective charts and the sales stood as the biggest unit week on both charts.<ref name=\"BBCH\"/> On the US charts, the album became the first to ever top the ''Billboard'' 200, [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]], [[Top Rap Albums]], Top Christian Albums and Top Gospel Albums at the same time.<ref name=\"Top5Charts\">{{cite web|last1=Zeller|first1=Xander|title=Kanye West Tops The Artist 100 Chart|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/8542710/kanye-west-tops-artist-100-chart|date=November 5, 2019|work=Billboard|accessdate=December 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191107035709/https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/8542710/kanye-west-tops-artist-100-chart|archive-date=November 7, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In its second week on the ''Billboard'' 200, ''Jesus Is King'' didn't remain atop the chart, falling to number two with 72,000 album-equivalent units, experiencing a 73% decline in sales.<ref name=\"BBDecline\"/> The album was replaced at the top position by  rapper [[Post Malone]]'s third studio album ''[[Hollywood's Bleeding]]'', which was number two on the ''Billboard'' 200 the previous week, and this marked its fifth week atop the chart.<ref name=\"BBDecline\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/8543199/post-malone-hollywoods-bleeding-earns-honor-atop-billboard-200|title=Post Malone's 'Hollywood's Bleeding' Earns Honor Atop Billboard 200 Not Achieved In Over a Year|work=Billboard|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=November 10, 2019|accessdate=November 10, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191110215008/https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/8543199/post-malone-hollywoods-bleeding-earns-honor-atop-billboard-200|archive-date=November 10, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n''Jesus Is King'' topped the [[Canadian Albums Chart]] with 16,000 total consumption units and 17.9 million on-demand streams that the units were mainly generated through.<ref name=\"fyi\">{{cite news|url=https://www.fyimusicnews.ca/articles/2019/11/03/jesus-king-weeks-albums-chart|title=Jesus Is King On This Week's Albums Chart|publisher=FYIMusicNews|date=November 3, 2019|accessdate=November 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191104165842/https://www.fyimusicnews.ca/articles/2019/11/03/jesus-king-weeks-albums-chart|archive-date=November 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The album stood as West's seventh number one album in Canada and his second consecutive chart topper.<ref name=\"fyi\"/> ''Jesus Is King'' debuted atop the [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Albums]] chart, giving West his third number one album in Australia and becoming his second consecutive chart topper, while standing as the first time that an album with the word \"King\" in its title reached the summit.<ref name=\"noise\"/> This stood as the 498th time that an album debuted atop the chart, though became the sixth for Def Jam and the 20th to do so in 2019.<ref name=\"noise\">{{cite news |title=Australian Charts: Kanye West 'Jesus Is King' Debuts At No 1 |url=http://www.noise11.com/news/australian-charts-kanye-west-jesus-is-king-debuts-at-no-1-20191102 |publisher=[[Paul Cashmere|Noise11]] |date=November 2, 2019 |accessdate=November 2, 2019}}</ref> The reign of the album at the top position continued into its second week on the ARIA Albums chart, giving West his first album to remain at number one for over a week in Australia and also leading to him ranking as 139th on the list of \"Accumulated Weeks at No.1: 1965 to 2019\", while placing West at number 16 for accumulated weeks at the chart's summit within the 2010s decade.<ref>{{cite news |title=Australian Charts: Kanye West 'Jesus Is King' Is No 1 For A Second Week |url=http://www.noise11.com/news/australian-charts-kanye-west-jesus-is-king-is-no-1-for-a-second-week-20191110 |publisher=Noise11 |date=November 10, 2019 |accessdate=February 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191206233747/http://www.noise11.com/news/australian-charts-kanye-west-jesus-is-king-is-no-1-for-a-second-week-20191110 |archive-date=December 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''Jesus Is King'' gave West his second chart-topping solo album in Norway by debuting at number one on the [[VG-lista|Norwegian Albums Chart]].<ref name=\"Norway\"/> A chart-topping debut was also attained by the album on the [[Hitlisten|Danish Albums]] chart, standing as West's second chart topper in Denmark.<ref name=\"den\"/> ''Jesus Is King'' debuted atop the [[Eesti Tipp-40|Estonia Tipp-40]], ending the seven-week reign of ''Hollywood's Bleeding''.<ref name=\"est\"/> The album also reached number one in [[Music of Iceland|Iceland]], [[International Federation of the Phonographic Industry|Latvia]] and [[Official New Zealand Music Chart|New Zealand]].<ref name=\"noise\"/><ref name=\"ice\"/><ref name=\"lat\"/>\n\n''Jesus Is King'' debuted at number two on the [[UK Albums Chart]], being blocked from the top spot by Welsh rock band [[Stereophonics]]' eleventh studio album ''[[Kind (album)|Kind]]''.<ref name=\"OCC\">{{cite news |last1=Copsey |first1=Rob |title=Stereophonics see off challenge from Kanye West to claim seventh UK Number 1 album |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/stereophonics-see-off-challenge-from-kanye-west-to-claim-seventh-uk-number-1-album__27647/ |publisher=[[Official Charts Company]] |date=November 1, 2019 |accessdate=November 1, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191101174701/https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/stereophonics-see-off-challenge-from-kanye-west-to-claim-seventh-uk-number-1-album__27647/ |archive-date=November 1, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, this gave West his sixth top ten album on the chart.<ref name=\"OCC\"/> The album also entered at number two on the [[Irish Albums Chart]], with it being prevented from becoming a chart topper by Irish singer-songwriter [[Dermot Kennedy]]'s debut studio album ''[[Without Fear (album)|Without Fear]]''.<ref name=\"press\"/> Despite this, ''Jesus Is King'' stood as the highest new entry of the week on the chart and West's sixth top ten album in Ireland.<ref name=\"press\">{{cite news |last1=Ransden |first1=Brenna |title=Dermot Kennedy continues his reign atop the Irish album charts, beating out Kanye West |url=https://www.hotpress.com/music/dermot-kennedy-continues-reign-atop-irish-album-charts-beating-kanye-west-22793266 |work=[[Hot Press]] |date=November 1, 2019 |accessdate=November 1, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191101200441/https://www.hotpress.com/music/dermot-kennedy-continues-reign-atop-irish-album-charts-beating-kanye-west-22793266 |archive-date=November 1, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> On the [[Sverigetopplistan]] albums chart, the album reached number two, tying with ''The Life of Pablo'' for West's highest charting album in Sweden, while reaching the same position on the [[AGATA (organization)|Lithuanian Albums]] chart.<ref name=\"Swe\"/><ref name=\"lit\"/> In the Netherlands, ''Jesus Is King'' peaked at number three on the [[Dutch Album Top 100]].<ref name=\"dut\"/> Similarly, the album charted at number four and five on the [[The Official Finnish Charts|Finnish Albums]] and Czech Albums charts, respectively.<ref name=\"finland\"/><ref name=\"cz\"/>\n\nAll eleven tracks from ''Jesus Is King'' charted on the US ''Billboard'' Hot 100, with \"Follow God\" debuting the highest at number seven.<ref name=\"hundred\"/> This made West the artist with the fifth-most songs in the history of the chart, with his total number of Hot 100 entries amounting to 107, while also leading to him ranking at number one on the US [[List of number-one artists on the Billboard Artist 100|''Billboard'' Artist 100]].<ref name=\"hundred\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/8542559/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-full-album-hot-100-chart|title=All 11 Songs From Kanye West's 'Jesus Is King' Album Debut on Hot 100|date=November 4, 2019|first=Xander|last=Zellner|work=Billboard|accessdate=November 6, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191105040719/https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/8542559/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-full-album-hot-100-chart|archive-date=November 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Top5Charts\"/> With the album, West simultaneously became the first artist to monopolize all top ten spots on the US [[Christian Songs]] and [[Billboard charts|Gospel Songs]] charts, respectively.<ref name=\"ETCanada\">{{cite web|title=Kanye West's 'Jesus Is King' Album Takes Over The Hot Christian And Gospel Songs Charts|url=https://etcanada.com/news/536938/kanye-wests-jesus-is-king-album-takes-over-the-hot-christian-and-gospel-songs-charts/|first=Corey|last=Atad|publisher=[[Entertainment Tonight Canada]]|date=November 7, 2019|accessdate=November 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191107193948/https://etcanada.com/news/536938/kanye-wests-jesus-is-king-album-takes-over-the-hot-christian-and-gospel-songs-charts/|archive-date=November 7, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Following the release of ''Jesus Is King'', three of the tracks entered the UK Singles Chart; this is the largest amount allowed by the [[Official Charts Company]] per artist at any one time, with \"Follow God\" charting the highest at number six.<ref name=\"McIntyre\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/hughmcintyre/2019/11/03/kanye-west-james-blunt-and-rick-astley-refresh-the-uk-top-10-with-new-albums/#2fe589a47658|title=Kanye West, James Blunt And Rick Astley Refresh The U.K. Top 10 With New Albums|work=Forbes|last=McIntyre|first=Hugh|date=November 3, 2019|accessdate=December 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191105163045/https://www.forbes.com/sites/hughmcintyre/2019/11/03/kanye-west-james-blunt-and-rick-astley-refresh-the-uk-top-10-with-new-albums/#2fe589a47658|archive-date=November 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Sequels==\n{{Main|Jesus Is Born|Jesus Is King Part II}}\nIn a pre-recorded promotional interview with [[Zane Lowe]] released a day before ''Jesus Is King'', West announced that an album by the Sunday Service Choir entitled ''[[Jesus Is Born]]'' would be released on December 25, 2019, to coincide with [[Christmas]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8540399/kanye-west-jesus-is-born-release-date|title=Kanye West Announces New 'Jesus Is Born' Album Before 'Jesus Is King' Even Drops|website=Billboard|date=24 October 2019|accessdate=5 December 2019|author=Lamarre, Carl|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191024201614/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8540399/kanye-west-jesus-is-born-release-date|archive-date=October 24, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> During a special [[Christmas Eve]] performance by the Sunday Service Choir, the director Jason White addressed the audience and reconfirmed the album's release date.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/kanye-west-and-sunday-service-confirm-jesus-is-born-drops-today-news.99151.html|title=Kanye West & Sunday Service Confirm \"Jesus Is Born\" Drops Today|website=HotNewHipHop|date=December 25, 2019|accessdate=December 25, 2019|author=Zidel, Alex|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191225175838/https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/kanye-west-and-sunday-service-confirm-jesus-is-born-drops-today-news.99151.html|archive-date=December 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Jesus Is Born'' was ultimately released on streaming services for Christmas afternoon on December 25, 2019. Klinkenberg viewed the album as the \"companion to ''Jesus Is King''.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/kanye-west-jesus-is-born-christmas-931238/|title=Kanye West Releases New Album 'Jesus Is Born'|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=December 25, 2019|accessdate=December 25, 2019|last1=Klinkenberg|first1=Brendan|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191225203938/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/kanye-west-jesus-is-born-christmas-931238/|archive-date=December 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn November 18, 2019, West announced on Twitter that he was working with American rapper and record producer [[Dr. Dre]] on a project entitled ''[[Jesus Is King Part II]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/11/kanye-west-dr-dre-jesus-is-king-part-2-announcement|title=Kanye West and Dr. Dre Announce 'Jesus Is King Part II'|author=Orwitz, Edwin|website=Complex|date=18 November 2019|accessdate=5 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191119134421/https://www.complex.com/music/2019/11/kanye-west-dr-dre-jesus-is-king-part-2-announcement|archive-date=November 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> During a December 2019 Sunday Service performance, West stated that he had always wished he could collaborate with Dr. Dre and added, \"Who knew all I had to do was do an album for God and then Dr. Dre would start mixing my beats? Spend your time on God, and he\u2019ll handle the rest.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/kanye-west-dr-dre-jesus-is-king-collab-explained/|title=Kanye West Reveals How He Convinced Dr. Dre to Collab on 'Jesus Is King Part II'|accessdate=5 December 2019|date=4 December 2019|website=Highsnobiety|author=Osei, Sarah|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191204172951/https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/kanye-west-dr-dre-jesus-is-king-collab-explained/|archive-date=December 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> That same month, Consequence confirmed that he was in Wyoming when asked about recording for ''Jesus Is King Part II''.<ref name=\"Cons\"/> On January 16, 2020, a snippet of \"[[Up from the Ashes (Kanye West and Dr. Dre song)|Up from the Ashes]]\" featuring production from Dr. Dre was leaked online.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://urbanislandz.com/2020/01/16/dr-dre-and-kanye-west-new-song-up-from-the-ashes-leaked-online/|title=Dr. Dre and Kanye West New Song \"Up From The Ashes\" Leaked Online|last1=Stephens|first1=M.|website=Urban Islandz|date=January 16, 2019|accessdate=January 17, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322194842/https://urbanislandz.com/2020/01/16/dr-dre-and-kanye-west-new-song-up-from-the-ashes-leaked-online/|archive-date=March 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nTrack listing and credits adapted from [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]].<ref name=\"Tidal\">{{cite web|url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/121012112|title=Jesus Is King / Kanye West|publisher=[[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]|accessdate=October 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191025183453/https://listen.tidal.com/album/121012112|archive-date=October 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| total_length = 27:04\n\n| title1 = [[Every Hour]]\n| note1 = featuring [[Sunday Service Choir]]\n| writer1 = {{hlist|[[Kanye West]]|Benjamin Scholefield|Federico Vindver|}}\n| extra1 = {{hlist|West|Budgie|Vindver|}}\n| length1 = 1:52\n\n| title2 = [[Selah (Kanye West song)|Selah]]\n| writer2 = {{hlist|West|[[Cyhi the Prynce|Cydel Young]]|[[Consequence (rapper)|Dexter Raymond Mills Jr.]]|Vindver|[[No Malice|Gene Thornton]]|Jahmal Gwin|Jeffrey LaValley{{ref|c|[c]}}|Rennard East|[[Pusha T|Terrence Thornton]]|[[E*vax|Evan Mast]]}}\n| extra2 =  {{hlist|West|[[E*vax]]|BoogzDaBeast{{ref|a|[a]}}|Vindver{{ref|a|[a]}}|[[Benny Blanco]]{{ref|b|[b]}}|[[Francis Farewell Starlite|Francis Starlite]]{{ref|b|[b]}}}}\n| length2 = 2:45\n\n| title3 = [[Follow God]]\n| writer3 = {{hlist|West|Aaron Butts|Bryant Bell|Calvin Eubanks{{ref|d|[d]}}|Curtis Eubanks{{ref|d|[d]}}|Gwin}}\n| extra3 = {{hlist|West|BoogzDaBeast|Xcelence}}\n| length3 = 1:45\n\n| title4 = [[Closed on Sunday]]\n| writer4 = {{hlist|West|Angel Lopez|Brian Miller|Chango Far\u00edas G\u00f3mez{{ref|e|[e]}}|Vindver|G. Thornton|East|T. Thornton|[[Timbaland|Timothy Mosley]]|Victory Elyse Boyd}}\n| extra4 = {{hlist|West|Lopez|Brian \"AllDay\" Miller|Vindver|[[Timbaland]]}}\n| length4 = 2:32\n\n| title5 = [[On God (Kanye West song)|On God]]\n| writer5